[{'created': '2013-09-08 03:00:51.000000000', 'message': "Don't add neutron metadata_nat_rules if disable metadata proxy

Neutron l3 agent will redirect 169.254.169.254 to neutron metadata
proxy port 9697 even though the neutron metadata proxy is disabled,
which will prevent redirecting to nova meatadata port 8775.

This patchset fixes this issue by adding a condition when adding nat
rules of neutron metadata proxy.

fixes bug #1212168

Change-Id: I99775aad73c49a8df3043690440d214614279a2b

fixes bug #1212168

"}]
commit_message:
Don't add neutron metadata_nat_rules if disable metadata proxy

This patchset fixes this issue by adding a condition when adding nat
rules of neutron metadata proxy.

fixes bug #1212168

Change-Id: I99775aad73c49a8df3043690440d214614279a2b

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-09-14 23:12:21.000000000', 'message': 'Install fedora grub from cached rpm during finalise

When uninstalling grub2, leave all its dependencies
including grub2-tools installed to minimise the number of packages
which need to be installed in the finalise stage.

Since the yum cache is unmounted during finalise, installing
grub2 in finalise is slowed by re-populating the yum cache.

This change copies the grub2 rpm out of the yum cache so it can be installed
from file during finalise.

This should prevent disk becoming full during finalise on Fedora.

Closes-Bug: #1217185

Change-Id: If095adc4abb52a19a3aa0b1caebfb3e4d8f605ef
'}]
commit_message:
Install fedora grub from cached rpm during finalise

When uninstalling grub2, leave all its dependencies
including grub2-tools installed to minimise the number of packages
which need to be installed in the finalise stage.

Since the yum cache is unmounted during finalise, installing
grub2 in finalise is slowed by re-populating the yum cache.

This change copies the grub2 rpm out of the yum cache so it can be installed
from file during finalise.

This should prevent disk becoming full during finalise on Fedora.

Closes-Bug: #1217185

Change-Id: If095adc4abb52a19a3aa0b1caebfb3e4d8f605ef

commit_message:
Move to new single heat.conf model

This also moves heat's logging to work more like the other OpenStack
services, so /var/log/heat will no longer be present.

Change-Id: I7ce5b8ace81931954849f0f2a3b53ad0572f7c64

commit_message:
Fix linked exception forming

There was a variable usage error in that 'exc_infos'
does not need to be three and also the exc_info[2] does
not need to be not-none if there is no traceback (which
is a valid usage/case of exc_info).

Change-Id: Iddb979e5cb7df424ee218854e0c766e5b45e3e29

commit_message:
Use executors instead of pools

A executor is a more generic concept than a pool and
also seems to work better with eventlet. This is also
a more supported model of performing concurrent operations
than using the mostly unknown multiprocessing thread
pool implementation.

Fixes: bug 1225275

Change-Id: I09e9a9000bc88cc57d51342b83b31f97790a62e9

commit_message:
VMProviderFactory.*_image() shouldn't be abstract

Seems like these methods will be often NotImplemented so it is better to
raise NotImplemented Exception than use @abstractmethod and have to implement
it in every subclass.

Certain plugin implementations of port binding depend on the port's
binding:host_id set by nova matching the compute node's hostname
reported by neutron agents in agents_db. Nova uses
socket.gethostname() to obtain the hostname, so this changes neutron
to also use socket.gethostname(), instead of socket.getfqdn() to
obtain the default hostname. If deployments require a specific

commit_message:
Use same hostname function as nova

Certain plugin implementations of port binding depend on the port's
binding:host_id set by nova matching the compute node's hostname
reported by neutron agents in agents_db. Nova uses
socket.gethostname() to obtain the hostname, so this changes neutron
to also use socket.gethostname(), instead of socket.getfqdn() to
obtain the default hostname. If deployments require a specific
hostname format or value, the hostname can be specified in nova and
neutron configuration files.

Closes-Bug: 1223000
Change-Id: I5de9c6b0df16eca482037a5bdc3a77dc52f4adba

commit_message:
Add missing options for setup-endpoints.

The *-password options need to be provided to getopt, otherwise
calling setup-endpoints and specifying these options fails.

Change-Id: I553a7ffbf5dea2d0f3429a3202d1a7b29ff1aa88

commit_message:
Add security_groups for create_port()

Currently if defined SecurityGroups and SubnetId properties for
instance in heat template, the SecurityGroups were not associated
to the port created within the previous SubnetId, in another word,
the instance are not allocated to the specified security groups
defined in heat template.

    * Modifies function _build_nics() in instance.py, adding an item
'security_groups' in the post body of create_port sending by neutronclient.
    * Adds a new function _get_security_groups_id() to map security_groups
names to ids.
    * Adds corresponding unit tests.

Fixes bug #1221564

Change-Id: Ica2df7c6f96bc982a5bd5ece3611949ae905e5c8

[{'created': '2013-09-13 20:55:37.000000000', 'message': 'Fixed "File Not Found" error on image in config-reference.

Configuration Reference build were displaying an error because one of
the references to an image in common content was missing an additional
level of the relative path:

[error] File not found:
'/home/sgordon/Source/openstack-manuals/doc/config-reference/common/figures/filteringWorkflow1.png'.
File is referred in
'/home/sgordon/Source/openstack-manuals/doc/config-reference/compute/section_compute-scheduler.xml'
fileRef='../common/figures/filteringWorkflow1.png'.

The fix was to change ../common/figures/ to ../../common/figures,
accounting for the additional level added to the path by the "compute"
directory in the configuration reference guide.

Change-Id: Ie3a4d8debc1008377ed90ba01bbf3a50fdef6a85
'}]
commit_message:
Fixed "File Not Found" error on image in config-reference.

Configuration Reference build were displaying an error because one of
the references to an image in common content was missing an additional
level of the relative path:

[error] File not found:
'/home/sgordon/Source/openstack-manuals/doc/config-reference/common/figures/filteringWorkflow1.png'.
File is referred in
'/home/sgordon/Source/openstack-manuals/doc/config-reference/compute/section_compute-scheduler.xml'
fileRef='../common/figures/filteringWorkflow1.png'.

The fix was to change ../common/figures/ to ../../common/figures,
accounting for the additional level added to the path by the "compute"
directory in the configuration reference guide.

Change-Id: Ie3a4d8debc1008377ed90ba01bbf3a50fdef6a85

commit_message:
Convert non-English exception message when a store loading error

In non-English environment when a store driver loading failed then a
BackendException will be raised with a non-ascii message. So we need
convert
any coded exception message to unicode string for logging.

This patch fixed a minor defect in
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/37421/
And the test case has be enhanced also.

Fixes bug 1202098

Related-Id: I9a58393b599aacc427cb4135988ecf5c3e90e455
Change-Id: I1cdc71537fc1205e5fa4ff9744b441e5d88c1d04
Signed-off-by: Zhi Yan Liu <zhiyanl@cn.ibm.com>

I wonder if we need to provide a failure and an error message rather than remove this functionality silently.

While we do know that using it this way is undocumented and likely to break, shipping this change suddenly could break somebody's template in a very subtle way without a clear way to debug. If I understand the change properly, we would start ignoring DependsOn in places we once respected it.

Also this seems like it would be worth of a bug report attached to a milestone since it is changing template parsing behavior."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-09-03 18:47:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Works for me

I really don't think we should have an error. You have the right to use the words "DependsOn" anywhere you like without Heat hitting you with a hammer and saying "No, you can't do that because once upon a time in the distant past we might have attached some special meaning to that, even though it was obviously in the wrong place to have that meaning."

Nobody is using this the wrong way. All of the example templates are correct. There's no logical place to put this other than where it belongs. This is just bringing the code in line with reality.'}, {'account_id': 6488, 'date': '2013-09-03 21:23:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

I respect your desire to land this and to make it as simple as possible.

We can't possibly know that "nobody is using this the wrong way." Nobody is required to tell us about their templates. The examples are moot, I'm talking about real automation that people may have rolled out on top of Heat.

I'd hope that we would see our early (but perhaps, quiet) users as the most valuable thing we have. If we do, then  it is worth helping them with a theoretical problem, especially one so easy to deal with.

If they have been shoving DependsOn in any old place, Heat has been creating a DependsOn relationship for them. I'd prefer that those templates error out now that we are changing the behavior. If not, users who have made this mistake will see no change, other than their template now starts racing where it did not before.

This is where template format versions are useful. If we make this heat template format version 2013-09-03 then we can just do the error for prior versions, and ignore a sub-resource DependsOn for templates who have specified the new version.'}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2013-09-03 22:07:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

I certainly agree that we want to avoid breaking user templates. However I also feel the risk is very, very, very low and the amount of extra complexity required to cope with it is disproportionately high.

At the end of the day, people don't write their templates by looking at the source code and trying to figure out the weirdest possible thing that could actually work. They use some combination of copying existing examples, reading the documentation and applying common sense (usually in that order)... none of which would lead to anyone having got this wrong."}, {'account_id': 4715, 'date': '2013-09-04 00:23:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

(1 inline comment)

I find that new little function very awkward to read.'}, {'account_id': 6488, 'date': '2013-09-04 01:01:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Zane, again, I understand that you want to move forward, however I'd prefer a calculated risk to a guess based on conjecture.

If you have some hard data to present, I could possibly be swayed, but from what I see, you are changing a long-broken-but-established interface. Since there has never been Heat documentation for the cloudformation bits, we can't claim "undocumented", as there are tons of things that are Heat only (like.. yaml) that don't apply to CloudFormation.

If this were a giant burden, I'd agree that it is worth the risk to ignore it. However, it is not difficult to provide a simple error message saying "you're using something that is only allowed at the resource root level".

Just ignore my -1 if you and others feel strongly about it.'}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2013-09-04 09:28:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: (1 inline comment)

I audited 31 uses of DependsOn in publicly available templates (in the example templates, unit tests and TripleO) and found 0 instances of it being in the wrong place.

Combining this (admittedly thin) empirical evidence with the theory (aka "conjecture") above (in a process commonly known as "science") leads me to the conclusion that the risk is low, though I grant that we are no closer to solving the ancient philosophical problem of induction (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Problem_of_induction).'}, {'account_id': 7385, 'date': '2013-09-05 07:08:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

'}, {'account_id': 6488, 'date': '2013-09-05 18:01:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Thanks for explaining further Zane. I do appreciate your position. The sample size is very small, and the known user base size is completely unknown. So the cost that would be incurred by any potential mishaps is unknown entirely.

However, the cost of producing an error is very tiny, miniscule really, so I stand at my position. I am sorry if this causes you distress, however without dissent we'll all just nod our way into a very dark place."}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2013-09-06 08:59:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Would posting a question on openstack-dev help, do you think? It's hard to know how many users are following that (most of the early ones were, but we are picking up steam now), but it would give us a bigger sample size."}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-09-14 06:03:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

commit_message:
Only look for DependsOn in the correct place

We used to search through the whole resource template snippet looking for
DependsOn, when really it should appear only at the top level. So as not to
encourage people to create templates that are (needlessly) incompatible
with CloudFormation, look only in the correct place.

Change-Id: I569fcb6d30bc498de253970f3df9119fdd9a0051

commit_message:
Do not overwrite snapshots

Overwriting snapshots can fail with out of disk space, which
causes the delete snapshot operation to fail. This is actually
a subset of of https://review.openstack.org/#/c/38172/, which
fixed this issues on master.

Change-Id: I6abcae49638ab19b05a03c0e80af1f7f83489aee
Fixes: Bug #1217859

commit_message:
Make InvalidQuotaValue a 403 rather than 409 error

InvalidQuotaValue does not really make sense as a 409 Conflict since
really it's more of a bad request. However, given the existing quota
extension API docs do not list 400 as a possible error response, use
NotAuthorized (which maps to 403 in the v2 API fault map) instead since
it's documented. Note that 409 is not documented as a possible response
code in the quota extension API docs.

http://docs.openstack.org/api/openstack-network/2.0/content/Update_Quotas.html

Closes-Bug: #1210274

Change-Id: I5ef6fe6986e20ca4f5958064c85d337cfc278940

I can see the issue here, and your fix will definitely address the problem, to some degree; however I am not entirely in agreement with the approach: by specifying False in neutron.conf, *all* new agents will come up with admin status down, until these are manually flipped on, after such validation occurs. If we want to invert the logic we need to restart the server. So I wonder if a more appropriate fix would be more appropriate where the *join-admin-up* property is something agent-specific (i.e. belongs to *-agent.ini). If you have N agents lined up to join and they are exactly alike, you will do:
1) make the first one join-admin-up=False, 2) do you validation; 3) update the admin-status of this agent to UP; 4) start all the other with join-admin-up=True and you're good to go."}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-09-14 06:03:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Fixes a bug where newly-discovered agents are assumed to be in

commit_message:
Adds a configuration option to disable new agents.

Fixes a bug where newly-discovered agents are assumed to be in
admin_state_up=True. This makes it difficult to verify that a new
network node is operating correctly, before routers and networks
are assigned to it. This fix makes the state configurable, with
'True' as the default.

Bug #1221713

Change-Id: I7f8f232ea2a4aa253a99f9b23b3afb58a49b1f87

commit_message:
Port test_server_actions into nova v3

This port server_test into v3. Add new server_client and
server_actions test for v3 api by inheritance. Also do
some changes in BaseComputeTest and client manager to
support nova v3 tests.

In nova v3 API there is no image API. So use glance
directly and change create_image use servers_client,
as it's server's action.

Partially implements blueprint nova-v3-api-tests

Change-Id: If6f9499a30e1704dc83ea14bbc1de4d5dca9ac63

commit_message:
Refactor test_agent_scheduler

Unit test for l3 agent scheduler and dhcp agent scheduler should be
seperated because:

- they are two different extensions, logically, they should be separated
- currently nvp doesn't support both of them, future plugin may not
  support both of them too (at least in the development process, it can
  happen)

Closes-Bug: #1220005
Change-Id: Ic65790cbb2ce9b9518770de39453195c143ef171

[{'created': '2013-08-30 22:14:02.000000000', 'message': "fix: find_one() running slow (MongoDB)

MessageController._next_marker() was modified in this patch in order
to allow hinting to make sure it is using the correct index. This
should ensure the query executes quickly.

_remove_expired() was similarly optimized since it would have the
same problem as _next_marker().

Finally, _list was changed to include limit in find() directly,

commit_message:
fix(storage.mongodb): find_one() running slow

MessageController._next_marker() was modified in this patch in order
to allow hinting to make sure it is using the correct index. This
should ensure the query executes quickly.

_remove_expired() was similarly optimized since it would have the
same problem as _next_marker().

Change-Id: Ib54dd12aafcd80e06ff72ee54ccce48bcaf62da8
Closes-Bug: #1218602

Add a pluggable solver scheduler

[{'created': '2013-09-11 19:17:27.000000000', 'message': 'Prevent stale DHCP directories for dhcp agent nodes

This change fixes an issue that is most acute in test/dev
environments but that may affect production environments
as well: the presence of DHCP directories that no longer
represent networks that exist in the Neutron DB. This
issue can manifest itself over time if you delete networks
from the Server while the Agent node is down.

Without this fix, at the agent start-up the method
existing_dhcp_networks will return an empty list, and
as a consequence the directories that belong to networks
that have been removed from the server will stay because
the sync logic will not process them as it only looks at
the mismatch between active networks on the agent and
active networks on the server. With the fix instead, we
return *all* existing dhcp networks; if they are meant to
be active, the agent will bring them up, if they no longer
exist on the server, then the agent will dispose of the
resources. The dnsmasq driver will do the right thing when
enabling or disabling the process.

Fixes bug #1195770

Change-Id: I194064a449801713051d01193adc706bcb687c82

commit_message:
Prevent stale DHCP directories for dhcp agent nodes

This change fixes an issue that is most acute in test/dev
environments but that may affect production environments
as well: the presence of DHCP directories that no longer
represent networks that exist in the Neutron DB. This
issue can manifest itself over time if you delete networks
from the Server while the Agent node is down.

Without this fix, at the agent start-up the method
existing_dhcp_networks will return an empty list, and
as a consequence the directories that belong to networks
that have been removed from the server will stay because
the sync logic will not process them as it only looks at
the mismatch between active networks on the agent and
active networks on the server. With the fix instead, we
return *all* existing dhcp networks; if they are meant to
be active, the agent will bring them up, if they no longer
exist on the server, then the agent will dispose of the
resources. The dnsmasq driver will do the right thing when
enabling or disabling the process.

Fixes bug #1195770

Change-Id: I194064a449801713051d01193adc706bcb687c82

commit_message:
Add a pluggable solver scheduler

This provides a solver scheduler, where complex constraints can be specified using pluggable solvers. An illustrative
implementation of a solver is included and is based on PULP. Here the constraints are based on the disk space and memory requirements,
and optimization is done using the host's free ram as a cost metric.

Change-Id: I2e4ebe4742dabdbc7d0cf41a8839438752b80c9c
Implements: blueprint solver-scheduler

commit_message:
Credentials Keystone V3 API Tests

This submission adds new test script 'test_credentials.py' so as
to verify CRUD Operations on Credentials API. And also added
required support functions in 'credentials_client.py' for both
JSON/XMl interfaces

Implements blueprint: add-credentials-test-keystone-v3

Change-Id: I00269eaeb01af821c47300a80d89fae3dd2598a2

commit_message:
Set example timestamps to 2038-01-18T21:14:07Z

This timestamp is the last possible moment that can be represented on
32-bit systems as an integer.

As a consequence of revising the JSON examples, the corresponding PEM
files must be re-generated as well.

Change-Id: Ic6014c08b4545db036605beef1e6a8829ed347c4
Related-Bug: 1190054
Related-Bug: 1225084

commit_message:
Move gettextutils installation in tests to core

gettextutils.install was done in tests/__init__.py, but this was
not consistent with how test environment setup is done. We have
code to set up the environment in core.py, so other environment
setup should be there. Also, this makes tests/__init__.py cleaner.

Change-Id: I762c8fa715e9c6ec26722fcd9b0ba0f9d613cb43

commit_message:
Use a local variable auditor_worker

This patch is only a cleanup, but our code makes me rage every time
I read it. In short, we have a class with a variable self.auditor,
and we assign ObjectAuditor to it at some ties, AuditorWorker at
other times. So, whenever there's a mismerge or whatever, you cannot
tell if self.auditor.broker_class makes sense or not.

Since all cases of using self.auditor as AuditorWorker are purely
local, just evict it to a local variable auditor_worker. Leave
self.auditor to represent ObjectAuditor, because it's used as
a class variable in places.

Change-Id: I811b80ac6c69a4daacfed7a5918bc0b15761d72e

commit_message:
Switched some relative imports to be absolute

Implicit relative imports don't work on Python3, and are also prone to
several different classes of errors.

Change-Id: I7b62e9bfbe9c0b1fc9876413e3139fda019a4e57

Temporary fix ceilometer-collector dpkg bug 1221945

solution works

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-07-15 21:44:10.000000000', 'message': "Implement message controller.

This patchset contributes a message controller for Marconi client. It
implements simple property querying for messages, as well as the
ability to reload these properties as needed (polling?) and delete a
message.

In order to meet these requirements, two new dependencies are added:
- flufl.enum
- six

flufl.enum adheres to the upcoming PEP 435 - enums in Python 3.4. It's
used to make Http interfaces safer to use and slightly easier to work
with.

six is used to boost py3k compat.

Note: This patchset was locally tested for py3k compatibility using
tox.

Change-Id: I287583ebff69c4571ae8164c99cff3b0628d23a1
"}, {'created': '2013-07-16 21:42:15.000000000', 'message': "Implement message controller.

"}, {'created': '2013-07-18 17:19:03.000000000', 'message': "Implement message controller.

This patchset contributes a message controller for Marconi client. It
implements simple property querying for messages, as well as the
ability to reload these properties as needed (polling?) and delete a
message.

In order to meet these requirements, two new dependencies are added:
- flufl.enum
- six

flufl.enum adheres to the upcoming PEP 435 - enums in Python 3.4. It's
used to make Http interfaces safer to use and slightly easier to work
with. The portion of this code that implements safe HTTP method
selection has been placed in openstack.common.

six is used to boost py3k compat.

This also introduces a directory structure for supporting multiple
transports. Instead of having a 'controller' dir, now we have a
'transports/http' and 'transports/zmq'.

Note: This patchset was locally tested for py3k compatibility using
tox.

Implements: blueprint messages-management
Change-Id: I287583ebff69c4571ae8164c99cff3b0628d23a1

message.

In order to meet these requirements, two new dependencies are added:
- flufl.enum
- six

flufl.enum adheres to the upcoming PEP 435 - enums in Python 3.4. It's
used to make Http interfaces safer to use and slightly easier to work
with. The portion of this code that implements safe HTTP method
selection has been placed in openstack.common.

six is used to boost py3k compat.

This also introduces a directory structure for supporting multiple
transports. Instead of having a 'controller' dir, now we have a
'transports/http' and 'transports/zmq'.

Note: This patchset was locally tested for py3k compatibility using
tox.

Implements: blueprint messages-management
Change-Id: I287583ebff69c4571ae8164c99cff3b0628d23a1

commit_message:
Implement message controller.

This patchset contributes a message controller for Marconi client. It
implements simple property querying for messages, as well as the
ability to reload these properties as needed (polling?) and delete a
message. It also uses the assumed structure of the HTTPclient that
will form the basis of the connection from the common libraries.

six is used to boost py3k compat.

This also introduces a directory structure for supporting multiple
transports. Instead of having a 'controller' dir, now we have a
'transports/http' and 'transports/zmq'.

Implements: blueprint messages-management
Change-Id: I287583ebff69c4571ae8164c99cff3b0628d23a1

commit_message:
task_state must be consider before many action

* Creating server status wait function for using with
  xml and json status wait.
* Considering fast status changes for BUILD status related tests.
  BUILD status wait can be useful when the server does
  not really need to be active for the test and we do not want to
  fail because the server reached the ACTIVE state before responding
  to the status query, due to rate limitation or for other reasons.
* Moving the wait function to new module, which could be used for
  collecting all wait related functionality.

  Fixing bug 1170118

Change-Id: Ie301124952412dab2b11a92a25ee54c633d08eeb

commit_message:
Ignore H803 from Hacking.

H803 checks for a period in commit messages, something the community
clearly rejected as a sensible check: periods in commit messages
should neither be rejected or required.

Change-Id: I866928c638d23a307f4c11b7cb947e88f90f1ab2

commit_message:
Need to allow quota values to be set to zero

There are test cases in tempest setting the value of quota to '0', we
need allow this scenario.

Fix bug 1191336

Change-Id: I205b523eddfcd3c253172ad4549142ceb9f9ee4e

Add tearDownClass to base swift test class

This commit fixes an oversight which was preventing isolated
credential cleanup on the swift tests.

commit_message:
Improves the parsing way of ssh returns

Huawei driver failed to parse ssh result when firstly logging
in storage system on paramiko 1.8.0. The update of paramiko
make the order of ssh returns changed. This patch improves
the parsing way of ssh returns.

This patch also does some changes for log punctuations.

fixes bug 1224499
Change-Id: Ia8761081dff998884f45312355b62aa27ab5417c

commit_message:
Test upgrade migration 16->17

This test covers the use case described in bug 1131590, where a
user_project_membership record cannot be upgraded past migration 16.

Closes-Bug: 1224320

commit_message:
pci passthrough fails while trying to decode extra_info

pci device with empty extra_info should use null dict instead of
None. keep the init of extra_info to make db could access it.

Closes-Bug: #1223559

Change-Id: I2e57eb53dfd4f5168d52dc94c2057fc575458aee
Signed-off-by: Yongli He <yongli.he@intel.com>

commit_message:
Merge changes to validate.py to test.py

The following changes were only applied to validate.py, apply them to
test.py as well:
* print process message
* Handle removed files in tools/validate.py
* Fix output of --force
* Don't descent into target dirs
* Update DocBook validating schema to 5.1CR1
* Add a tiny bit more verbosity

Change-Id: Ia3ee355e0e87c5748d83ae670ca845ee30d9646d

commit_message:
Adds disk_format parameter to upload_volume method in volumes client

Adds a third parameter, disk_format, to the upload_volume method of
the volumes client. The parameter is also added to the Tempest
configuration and defaults to "raw" if not set.

Closes-Bug: #1218666
Change-Id: I6c62796161c9219cbd80eb9fecc7fbb0f3a4681a

commit_message:
Add handoffs_first and handoff_delete to obj-repl

If handoffs_first is True, then the object replicator will give
partitions that are not supposed to be on the node priority.

If handoff_delete is set to a number (n), then it will delete a handoff
partition if at least n replicas were successfully replicated

Also fixed a couple of things in the object replicator unit tests and
added some more

DocImpact

Change-Id: Icb9968953cf467be2a52046fb16f4b84eb5604e4

commit_message:
Fix client connection leaks in HP3PAR drivers

In the presence of exceptions, hp3parclient connections
did not get closed. This fix adds try/finally blocks
around all client login/logout calls.

Change-Id: I105b06cea5e61f3e9cf0d6e19c7ce430fedad715
Closes-Bug: 1220948

'}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2013-09-13 14:38:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

This is a quick fix, but have you considered breaking down NSXRouterExtAttributes into multiple attribute classes? Otherwise every time there is a migration, both plugins must be defined, even though that's not really necessary."}, {'account_id': 261, 'date': '2013-09-13 15:14:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Breaking into multiple classes will cause distinct table mappings, unless we do some sqlalchemy trick that at the moment I'm not aware of.

And distinct table mappings will mean two joins instead of one on each query. Paying the price of a join for a single attributes seems a bit excessive to me compared with the uglyness of having to remember of adding both plugin to any migration involving this table.

I think it is fine to have a single table for attributes; eventually the two plugins will converge so this issue will not exist anymore."}, {'account_id': 2592, 'date': '2013-09-13 15:40:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

Add NvpPluginV2 to migration 4a666eb208c2

Bug 1224882

This migration alters a table used by NvpPluginV2 as well, so
it must be included in the plugin list.

Change-Id: Ifc5104d813c76fa8de000ec977ca3242e90e433d

commit_message:
Use the generic RequestLimitExceeded exception when possible

Rather than having lots of specific exceptions that all pertain to request
limitation, we can just use the RequestLimitExceeded exception when applicable,
which can also simplify the handling of exception mapping in fault.py.

Change-Id: I61b1e59912087fad286e74c22af15ffe6382bb65

Aside from the fact that I think min()ing or max()ing the uptime from a set of hosts that hide behind a single compute node is ugly and wrong, I have another question.

Can you explain why there are three implementations of this function in this patch? Looks like two that survey a group of hosts and return integer seconds, and one that does so for a single host and returns a string."}, {'account_id': 1561, 'date': '2013-09-11 13:46:08.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 12:

And actually ... maybe this should just be a stub that returns 0.  None of this makes any sense.  It doesn't seem like a useful value to return at all.  It seems better to make that obvious."}, {'account_id': 1653, 'date': '2013-09-11 14:33:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 12:

Hi,
After the comments, which actually make a lot of sense, I have written that the function will return that the user should access the host to get the uptime. So it will be as follows:
nicira@os-devstack:~$ nova hypervisor-uptime 1
+---------------------+--------------------------------------------+
| Property            | Value                                      |
+---------------------+--------------------------------------------+
| uptime              | Please refer to 10.127.1.40 for the uptime |
| id                  | 1                                          |
| hypervisor_hostname | domain-c7(Cluster31)                       |
+---------------------+--------------------------------------------+
nicira@os-devstack:~$ 
I hope that that suffices - the administrator is the one who uses the command so they will be able to actually access the host and gather all of the details that they need
Thanks
Gary'}, {'account_id': 1653, 'date': '2013-09-11 14:35:39.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 13.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-09-11 15:04:37.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 13: Works for me

commit_message:
VMware: fix driver support for hypervisor uptime

This method was previously not implemented and would throw an exception
with the tempest tests. It will now redirect the administrator to access
the host to het the uptime.

Fixes bug 1199946

Change-Id: I073f50fee6aa76e912753c0754d632ff2adfa287

commit_message:
Get image properties instead of the whole image

When booting an instance using the new BDMv2 API we can specify to boot
from a volume created from an image on the fly. In this case the API
should pass the image properties to the new instance so it can get some
important parameters that it might specify.

After adding the new BDMv2 API in 13180f76, we introduced a mistake in
the method that gets the image properties (from the boot BDM) if no
image_ref is defined. When the source is an image it will return the
whole image metadata instead of getting just the properties. This
causes that when the source image is an AMI the instance won't have the
ramdisk and kernel properties set and will fail to boot.

This patch fixes the image properties when booting from a volume created
from an image.

Fixes bug #1220318

Change-Id: Ibcd60510cc909fcaa0d6d4769f91c070dfaf22ff

commit_message:
Ensure default TTL is respected by PowerDNS backend

Previousally, all records without an explict TTL were defaulting to 3600
regardless of the per-zone default.

Change-Id: Idbfaad5303e05dfdc7bcbb371dd69d3e4f988a7c

commit_message:
Update Ceilometer alembic requirement to 0.6.0 version

Our ceilometer/storage/sqlalchemy/alembic/versions/b6ae66d05e3_remove_extra_indexes.py call a new drop_constraint method with type_ argument,
but this new method argument is invovled from alembic 0.5.0 version, Jenkins is using alembic 0.6.0 version

Fixed bug: 1221467

Change-Id: I78f1e538c39fe4c972f21aa0fe77d3c82087176a

subject: Hash device_id only if it is longer than the allowed MAX size for NVP
messages:
[{'account_id': 261, 'date': '2013-08-22 08:14:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: (2 inline comments)

I am not sure what we should do with this part of the code.
At some point I was even thinking of removing this tag, but I'm not sure if there are external tools relying on it - in that case we should leave it as it is, deprecate it, and use another tag.

I agree that if the purpose of the tag is informational, hashing does not make any sense. Also if the tag is called vm_id perhaps we can just populate it for instance and avoding populating it for dhcp and router interfaces.

Just my 2p..."}, {'account_id': 748, 'date': '2013-08-22 14:34:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: (2 inline comments)

We cannot tell for sure if this tag has been used or not and removing/renaming it is more trouble than it's worth IMO (because we need to use more complex queries to retrieve ports by device id based on the old and the new tag). The idea of tagging ports just for VM's is interesting but then again we'd be unable to retrieve _all_ ports with a filter set to device_id. I thought this one was the best course of action to deal with concerns I have heard from the field."}, {'account_id': 4395, 'date': '2013-08-27 23:43:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

commit_message:
Hash device_id only if it is longer than the allowed MAX size for NVP

This ensure that a VM uuid stays untouched, avoiding potential
confusion when inspecting NVP port tags. This patch also abstracts
the hashing method out by introducing a device_id_to_vm_id method.
Filtering logic is preserved, and a test has been added to ensure
that. However such a logic is not currently used in the NeutronPlugin
(because of the introduction of async status updates), but it has
been added as utility method to nvplib.

Fixes bug #1215204

Change-Id: Ib96ecae438e30f195c8b45176abc1cf55b4b363f

commit_message:
Add a --force option

This is a useful debugging and/or system fixer tool for instances where
metadata has not changed but one needs to re-run the configuration.

Fixes bug #1223693

Change-Id: I62b097bafa339fefcf6e03d11636f5ab622fb71a

commit_message:
Fixes the use of exception.InvalidInput with the wrong arguments

A mapping key of 'message' in exception.InvalidInput is 'reason'.
cinder/volume/drivers/netapp/iscsi.py and
cinder/volume/drivers/netapp/utils.py had used 'data'.

Change-Id: Ie40fc2f954984350827414edee9226adc80c8033
Closes-Bug: #1224790

commit_message:
Always log stdout and stderr of CLI commands

Currently it was logged only when cli subprocess call itself
failed, so there was not enough debug output when asserts/test cases
failed.

Also fixes invalid log.warning on newline at the end of ascii table.

For backport - as stderr was always merged to stdout in grizzly time
 - corresponding parts of the patch were removed.

(cherry picked from commit 0d9a84fb614fc65fa4417d1103d051a9580555df)

Conflicts:
	cli/__init__.py

Change-Id: I5251a06018e8bf79c30ad84f8f0ed8aac797f832

commit_message:
Add default_availability_zone configuration option to cinder

This option is used to specify the default AZ for the whole service. So when
creating a new volume this value is used to specify the AZ of a volume.

Previously we were overloading the use of the storage_availability_zone option
which is also used to specify what AZ a service belongs to. We still fail back
on the storage_availability_zone when creating a new volume if the
default_availability_zone is not set.

Fixes bug: 1221260

Change-Id: Iec381f50c9aeb4a0abbcaa1d7b0107de09a73544

commit_message:
Add shell variables instead of ID values

Updates "Setting up tenants, users, and roles - manually"
section of the keystone install guide with shell variables
for each of the IDs referenced.
Fixed formatting by adding <screen><prompt>$</prompt> around <userinput>
Formatting: Replaced \t with whitespace, changed <literal> id Value
</literal> to <literal>id</literal> value, changed users to user's.

Change-Id: I4385d322a7b739cf78bc420c5617e69c01eb2810
Closes-Bug: #1073383

commit_message:
Add logging to the python-clients

The python-clients are very different in how they are logging,
the cinder and nova clients needs and additional option.

This change enables the http request/response logging to the
 nova and cinder python client.

The nova and cinder python client wants to create unnecessary logger
 to the console, unless you add a handler earlier.

Change-Id: I5bc72e52d16d2380ee36c8586cd1694ac1b4fa3d

commit_message:
Stop doing special things with setuptools

pip 1.4 can handle the distribute/setuptools upgrade sequencing
appropriate. So it turns out all we need to upgrade is pip, and then the
rest will fall in to place. This will still not fix the packages vs. pip
interactions, but we don't to muck with the system setuptools packages
at all.

Change-Id: I99220ccc190798c3eb77bb2361abc6606bd546b4

    * Rename --ca-file to --os-cacert (--ca-file deprecated for
      backward compatibility)
    * Add cacert to keystoneclient initialization to verify the
      keystone server certificate

    This aligns ceilometerclient with keystoneclient for option naming
    and the use of TLS for the keystone auth connection.  It does not
    change the use of TLS/SSL for the glance connection.

Change-Id: I81cbbffd2b2b05bc3660e752e7543371c3fe5887
Closes-Bug: #1224343
'}]
commit_message:
Support --os-cacert
    * Rename --ca-file to --os-cacert (--ca-file deprecated for
      backward compatibility)
    * Add cacert to keystoneclient initialization to verify the
      keystone server certificate

    This aligns ceilometerclient with keystoneclient for option naming
    and the use of TLS for the keystone auth connection.  It does not
    change the use of TLS/SSL for the glance connection.

Change-Id: I81cbbffd2b2b05bc3660e752e7543371c3fe5887
Closes-Bug: #1224343

commit_message:
Make field validation to be conditional.

Introduce new field attribute 'enabled' - true by default, but if it
is false, then the field won't be validated, only coerced to Python
type. This actually solves the issue with hidden (and disabled) fields
which don't validate and prevent proceeding to next step.

Change-Id: Ie57fa4731792ed1e44e9f61fa5cb6a16ddaf3109
Fixes: bug MRN-883

commit_message:
Make field validation to be conditional.

Introduce new field attribute 'enabled' - true by default, but if it
is false, then the field won't be validated, only coerced to Python
type. This actually solves the issue with hidden (and disabled) fields
which don't validate and prevent proceeding to next step.

Cherry-picked from release0.2, Ie57fa4731792ed1e44e9f61fa5cb6a16ddaf3109
Fixes: bug MRN-883

Change-Id: I4fc438a8949957800fcd0ac55bb30cd62744b1e0

[{'created': '2013-09-12 11:34:06.000000000', 'message': 'Migrate remaining TEXT columns to LONGTEXT

To avoid cases where mysql silently truncates json data
when it is > 2^16 bytes, migrate all remaining TEXT columns
to LONGTEXT, in a similar way to the fix for bug #1210799

Combined with the fix for bug #1215501 which limits the request
body size, we should never truncate, even if mysql is configured
such that it can happen

Fixes bug #1223029

Change-Id: Ib536cfa8e2952a5e047cd8573288cdd9fee0622c
'}]
commit_message:
Migrate remaining TEXT columns to LONGTEXT

To avoid cases where mysql silently truncates json data
when it is > 2^16 bytes, migrate all remaining TEXT columns
to LONGTEXT, in a similar way to the fix for bug #1210799

Combined with the fix for bug #1215501 which limits the request
body size, we should never truncate, even if mysql is configured
such that it can happen

Fixes bug #1223029

Change-Id: Ib536cfa8e2952a5e047cd8573288cdd9fee0622c

commit_message:
Fix incorrect NotImplementedError

neutron.common.exceptions doesn't define NotImplementedError, but
some codes still use it. We should use builtin
exceptions.NotImplementedError instead.

Note: this patch also fixes a never run code in nvp.

Closes-Bug: #1221500
Change-Id: I5f367ab5edc1e7fbbc2e4eba5fe36d148d4d062d

commit_message:
Fixing UnicodeEncodeError against volume creating function

When creating a volume with non-English characters and there is
not enough space for it, then an UnicodeEncodeError occurs. So
we need convert any coded exception message to unicode string
for logging.

Fixes bug 1223128

Change-Id: If1d4faad2bcde696f20565deb01226de33caccad

commit_message:
Turn db model object into a primitive object to avoid error

In volume API controller we need turn db model object into a primitive
object to avoid error when it adding visible administrator metadata to
volume's metadata dict.

Fixes bug: 1220232

Change-Id: I5f6c4fc8dd6ca3af02db577b37dcaeee92bb42e5
Signed-off-by: Zhi Yan Liu <zhiyanl@cn.ibm.com>

commit_message:
Do not reschedule if copy_image_to_volume fails

Catch any exception raised by copy_image_to_volume and wrap them
in ImageCopyFailure. Raising ImageCopyFailure will prevent
the volume from being rescheduled.

Fixes: bug #1224211
Change-Id: I1366f86927813cadefe742769eb7cff27ed41b7e

IRC discussion seems to indicate that this approach is less desirable than some alternatives. Marking this -2 to avoid other reviewers spending time on it until we reach a consensus.'}, {'account_id': 5441, 'date': '2013-09-03 17:42:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 14: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I think we should find a way to expose remote access to the resource tracker, but I don't think RPC calls to compute like this are going to work.

The main issue I see with this is that aborting claims won't work because the claim stores a copy of the in memory resource tracker in its class.  One it goes over RPC it can't update properly on an abort().

I think a good approach would be to persist the resource tracker somewhere off the compute node so it can be accessed remotely without a roundtrip to the compute.  Having it on the compute offers easy synchronization so a new mechanism for that would need to be worked out.

In my mind what we want to optimize is speed of scheduling so the conductor can very quickly discard computes that won't be able to hold an instance."}, {'account_id': 1561, 'date': '2013-09-05 12:46:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 14: Do not merge

commit_message:
Exposes compute rt.resize_claim through compute.rpcapi

ResourceTracker is a compute specific thing and thus we
need to expose resize_claim method via compute.rpcapi to
be accessible on conductor when we move cold migration
code to there.

Partially implements bp cold-migrations-to-conductor

Change-Id: I01233ac32b740936f059907313550a17fef2c164

commit_message:
Refactoring of FC volume attach/detach

This patch adds the cinder brick library into nova.
It also refactors the kvm libvirt volume driver
to use the new brick connector object.
This also refactors the way we fetch the iscsi
initiator information and the fibre channel
wwns and wwpns.

A follow up patch will include the refactoring of
the kvm libvirt iSCSI volume driver.

Once this lands in Nova, we will push to have brick
accepted into OSLO.

blueprint refactor-iscsi-fc-brick

Change-Id: Ie3723e923e89fcaf1f6b33e15935e0c9c4d8e2df

commit_message:
Unify aggregate-based conf overrides in scheduler

Move the common logic of overriding conf options with aggregate metadata
from AggregateCoreFilter and AggregateRamFilter to ConfAggregateOverride.

Partially implements blueprint multiple-scheduler-drivers

Change-Id: Ie8ab4ddf171ec74346b581227a8cdf0183e86b54

commit_message:
Extend conf overrides to support more opt types

Add generic support for StrOpt, ListOpt, IntOpt and BoolOpt.
Required for supporting other filters overriding conf options
with aggregate metadata.

Partially implements blueprint multiple-scheduler-drivers

Change-Id: I6fa1ebb29b4f311a2e6bfcdb799d48d76e02e3a7

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-07-04 10:48:09.000000000', 'message': "Enhance the vCenter driver to support FC volume attach

Attaching of a fibre channel LUN to an instance on ESX is enabled
by providing the details of the host's HBA wwnn(s) and wwpn(s) to
cinder. Cinder driver inturn provides the target wwpn and wwnn,
lun id of the target. This is used by the ESX nova driver
to attach the LUN to the instance

This patch addresses the the following points of the blueprint,
1. Enhance the vCenter driver to support FC volume attach to
   instances created on ESX
2. Support HP Cinder 3Par driver

If the instance is hosted in a cluster, then the presentation
of the LUN is done only to the host on which the instance is
hosted.

Presenting to multiple hosts will be implemented as a separate
patch

Change-Id: I7dbc57db5c669b447c2c13687621469f79f90d0f
Blueprint: fc-support-for-vcenter-driver

commit_message:
Enhance the vCenter driver to support FC volume attach

Attaching of a fibre channel LUN to an instance on ESX is enabled
by providing the details of the host's HBA wwnn(s) and wwpn(s) to
cinder. Cinder driver inturn provides the target wwpn and wwnn,
lun id of the target. This is used by the ESX nova driver
to attach the LUN to the instance

This patch addresses the the following points of the blueprint,
1. Enhance the vCenter driver to support FC volume attach to
   instances created on ESX
2. Support HP Cinder 3Par driver

If the instance is hosted in a cluster, then the presentation
of the LUN is done only to the host on which the instance is
hosted.

Presenting to multiple hosts will be implemented as a separate
patch

Change-Id: I7dbc57db5c669b447c2c13687621469f79f90d0f
Blueprint: fc-support-for-vcenter-driver

Add AggregateDiskFilter

Implements blueprint per-aggregate-resource-ratio

* AggregateDiskFilter to support per-aggregate disk_allocation_ratio
* Falls back to global setting if per-aggregate value not found

DocImpact

Change-Id: I441bb962aee715bab829991519c7233ffefa4bbb

commit_message:
Sanitize env variable for passlib

Sanitize the env variable PASSLIB_MAX_PASSWORD_SIZE
when the keystone starts. It will get rid of the
potential PasswordSizeError and unexpected security
issues of passlib.

Change-Id: I7140619a9288385471dd837fa3de0e0063605e01
Fixes: bug #1175905

commit_message:
Add event/trait type queries

This patch adds storage queries for traits and
event types. Queries added in this patch set:

 * get_event_types - returns all event_types in
   the database. This is simply a string.
 * get_trait_types - returns all trait_types
   filtered by event_type.
 * get_traits - returns all trait data for an
   event_type, and an optional trait_type name.

In order to accomodate the new trait type table,
the storage model for trait is refactored, and a
new TraitType model is added. This model is necessary
because the api will provide a way to query trait
types without returning all trait data. Without
the TraitType model, there is no good way to return
a list of trait (name, data type) pairs to the api.

partial-bp specify-event-api

Change-Id: I6dcb26c1137692fc9a0dcc9770a53928666ab754

are groupby and reset_on mutually exclusive? seems like if both are set, in some cases it'll go down reset_on path and in other places it'll go down groupby path"}, {'account_id': 8122, 'date': '2013-09-03 19:06:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 11: (3 inline comments)

reset_on and groupby are mutually exclusive, indeed. I think I'll add something like:

if groupby and reset_on:
    raise NotImplementedError(...)"}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2013-09-03 19:38:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11:

How is this different from the groupby operation?'}, {'account_id': 8122, 'date': '2013-09-03 20:05:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11:

"Group By" is a just like the SQL operation, iiuc.

"Reset on" just computes multiple set of statistics.

For instance, if you use the "period" parameter (period=p), instead of getting one set of statistics as the output, you will get many:

Set #0 (from 0 to p)
Set #1 (from p to 2p)
Set #2 (from 2p to 3p)
...


When using "reset_on=foo", the statistics will be broken into multiple sets of statistics, for instance:

Set #0 (foo == 'bar')
Set #1 (foo == 'baz')
Set #2 (foo == 'bar')

Note that sets #0 and #2 have the same value of 'foo'. This is because stats are "grouped" together only if consecutive values of 'foo' are similar. Here, the sample list might have been (in the time interval [t0:t5]):

t0 {... 'foo': 'bar', ...}
t1 {... 'foo': 'bar', ...}
t2 {... 'foo': 'bar', ...}
t3 {... 'foo': 'baz', ...}
t4 {... 'foo': 'bar', ...}
t5 {... 'foo': 'bar', ...}

This is especially useful to compute certain kinds of stats. A good example might be the uptime of a VM. If one needs the total uptime of a VM for a given month, they might have samples such as :

t0 {..., 'state': 'active', ... }
...
t_shutdown {..., 'state': 'shutdown', ... }
...
t_power_on {..., 'state': 'active', ...}
...
t_x {..., 'state': 'active', ...}

Computing stats with 'reset_on=state' will give the following results:

Set #0 (state=active)
Set #1 (state=shutdown)
Set #2 (state=active)

From there, computing the total uptime is easy.'}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2013-09-03 22:16:58.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 11:

OK, what you're describing is how I thought group_by would work. I'm not entirely certain how group_by is useful in this API if it *doesn't* work that way. :-)"}, {'account_id': 8122, 'date': '2013-09-03 22:28:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11:

I think "group by" would only return two sets of statistics for my last example: one with "status=active" and one with "status=shutdown" (well, I'm not sure groupby currently works with metadata, but you get the idea). I think Julien and Terry could tell us more.'}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2013-09-03 22:30:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 11:

Yep, I see that as a valid but not terribly useful definition of group-by. But maybe that's just me. I'll try to review this change more closely this evening, but any potential objection I had based on the apparent duplication is gone. :-)"}, {'account_id': 2472, 'date': '2013-09-04 00:15:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 11: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

commit_message:
Implement 'reset_on' for mongodb

When given a 'reset_on' parameter equal to the name of one of the
resource_metadata fields, the get_meter_statistics() will return a list of
statistics such that every one of its elements refer to consecutive samples
that have the same value in this field.

blueprint uptime-measurement
Change-Id: Id2bf1c1d15e7498a9625a6f15a074c5338e74d59

commit_message:
Invert the reschedule exception list

Instead of having a list of exceptions that would be
checked to avoid rescheduling instead have a list of
exceptions that will cause rescheduling. This list will
be much smaller than a blacklist and likely will have
to be expanded as new failure modes that should attempt
rescheduling are found & whitelisted.

Change-Id: I164bf8f290680ae1edb3ad77b59cd555b969fc4d

iccha, thanks for the review. Yes, I'm aware of 37184. But just like I discussed with markwash. I'm still porting the oslo rpc part in my fix, because:
1. bug 1201695 tracked by 37184 is a duplicate of bug 1020749 tracked by this fix.
2. There are some new changes of olso rpc code, I really want to make sure my fix is based on the latest rpc version. Since my fix is using the oslo notifier to replace current Glance notifier code. And I believe it would be better to keep these code in one fix to make sure the overall notifier works fine."}, {'account_id': 6549, 'date': '2013-07-18 04:00:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

I have little same concerns for this, why we not port original oslo.rpc in a dedicated change firstly (such as #37184) and after that you adding needed changes in here base on it?'}, {'account_id': 6159, 'date': '2013-08-16 09:20:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6: Do not merge

Please, don't take the -2 too harshly.

I think we should let this patch land as part of the Ith release. Along with this migration, I also think we could improve existing notifications and emit some stats based on current usage.

There's a similar discussion going on in the m-l right now: http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2013-August/013492.html

Also, most of this code will have to be changed / replaced once oslo.messaging becomes full featured. I'd rather wait for Oslo's migration to land.

Thanks for taking care of this."}, {'account_id': 1669, 'date': '2013-08-21 15:16:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

Better to have well tested code than old (bugged) one for Havana. Flavio, as discussed on IRC, would you mind reseting your score? :)'}, {'account_id': 2813, 'date': '2013-08-21 15:54:11.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

The problem with the actual rpc layer of glance is it doesn't support the rabbitmq 'x-ha-policy: all' and/or multiple rabbitmq_hosts.

So in ceilometer (or anything that consume glance notification) when you configure rabbitmq with 'x-ha-policy: all', you can retrieve notification from every components except glance. Because a queue created without 'x-ha-policy: all' cannot be read with kombu configured with 'x-ha-policy: all' and vice vesa. So actually, you need to make a choice between rabbitmq HA queue or the glance notification in ceilometer.

This problem already exists in grizzly, I have imagined it will be fixed for havana. 

I hope this argue will help to have this merged."}, {'account_id': 616, 'date': '2013-08-22 01:40:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

From the perspective of current deployers of glance who don't know or care about rabbit ha, this change breaks configuration for no benefit.

So at a minimum we should figure out how to not break configuration of glance. notifier_strategy = <whatever> should continue to work, though I think we can mark the config as deprecated.

Its also a bit skeptical that the ha support is important enough to be disruptive. Can someone give me a sense of how many folks want or need it, vs how many are not concerned?"}, {'account_id': 2813, 'date': '2013-08-22 06:54:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

I agree the configuration must be backward compatible. But this is just a classic review remark, easily to fix, not a argue for not merging this.'}, {'account_id': 616, 'date': '2013-08-22 17:08:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

Mehdi, You are right. I agree.

Also, this does of course fix our bug as well, so I see the value in this patch now (after Fei Long's gentle reminder)."}, {'account_id': 2813, 'date': '2013-08-22 17:14:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

commit_message:
Use Openstack common notifier

Now most of the OpenStack projects has replaceed the notification
code with Oslo's. This fix is using to track the change and
refactors the unit test code of notifier.

DocImpact
Fix bug 1020749

Change-Id: If3cd72e9e580ff9fbd1bbae8bd1493529e01a2a7

commit_message:
Refactor OAuth consumer/token client instances

As per changes in keystoneclient, the manager referenced should
be prefixed with oauth_, as the terms consumers and tokens could
potentially be used in another context.

(3 inline comments)

I started reviewing this and it generally looks good.  I like the concept and all of that.  I left some small comments and then came across a fairly significant issue that isn't the fault of the authors of the patch.  It's just the timing.

While this has been developed, another effort has been going on, the unified-objects blueprint.  This is about decoupling nova from the db schema, and part of that is to kill off all of the places where we're returning sqlalchemy models to the rest of nova and replace them with our own objects.

This is beneficial and required for some important efforts, such as our long road to good support for rolling live upgrades.

A lot of progress has been made, and there's still a lot to do.  I think we need to start requiring that new APIs work this way, instead of returning db models.  Take a look at this blueprint:

https://blueprints.launchpad.net/nova/+spec/compute-api-objects

This is converting nova.compute.api to return objects of this type.  I'd like to see this new api, nova.compute.instance_groups_api work this same way.  Unfortunately, that's going to be a good bit of work and will push this out to havana-3."}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2013-07-09 22:13:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 14:

Yeah, I agree with Russell. This is adding a new file and a new set of APIs providing an abstraction for a unit. This fits perfectly with the Objects, and would save us the churn of putting this in and then just converting it shortly thereafter.

It'd be great to see this go in as object-native from the start."}, {'account_id': 681, 'date': '2013-07-09 22:16:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 14:

Hi Dan, Russell

Thanks for your detailed feedback and I agree ....

However do you think it might be ok to merge this so that it gets some use between H2 and H3 while I rework the code for the new compute API objects? I am inheriting it from Senhua who wrote the code for this patch and is now moving on. This way his commit can help us test the API etc while I work as per your suggestions for H3.

regards
debo'}, {'account_id': 7494, 'date': '2013-07-15 03:07:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 14:

Can we merge the code first so that others can use this feature for some internal development?'}, {'account_id': 681, 'date': '2013-07-15 04:01:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 14:

It would be nice to merge the API so that the rest of the scheduler code that has been already merged by garyk can be leveraged for internal tests etc. However RussellB and DanS strongly believe that 1) once this is merged there will be less commitment to merge the new version :) 2) the right way to do it is to use the API objects. 

Happy to rework the code to use API objects but it would be **very** nice if this could be merged. The new code would still get committed etc as per the review feedback!'}, {'account_id': 782, 'date': '2013-07-19 12:58:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 14: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Sorry, I am agreed with Russell on this rally. We had to draw a line in the sand, and yes the for you the timing of that sucks. Really sorry.

So two things:
- all new rest apis get a v2 and v3 version

Add REST API for instance group api extension

Support the Creation, Read, Update, Delete, and List of instance group

Refactored the code to use objects (https://review.openstack.org/#/c/38979/)

commit_message:
Remove version pins from setup_requires

setuptools can never upgrade things based on setup_requires versions.
What this means is that pbr can NEVER EVER introduce a feature or a
change that would require specifying a newer version of pbr in the
setup.py file, because if will break. This is a non-flexible
requirement.

The requirements.txt file can catch the actual version we're interested
in having around, if it's an install time requirement.

Change-Id: Ic491f295156ea0ee3f6296360ca8b31d5134ae07

so auth_uri != %(auth_protocol)s://%(auth_host)s:%(auth_port)d/

a correct example is glance:

[{'created': '2013-06-24 04:24:03.000000000', 'message': 'Replace HttpConnection in auth_token with Requests.

Requests is becoming the standard way of doing http communication, it
also vastly simplifies adding other authentication mechanisms. Use it in
the auth_token middleware.

Also introduces HTTPretty for testing. This allows mocking based on a
URL rather than stubbing a particular library. It also provides greater
transparency into what locations are actually being mocked and with what
data.

I think it would be good to adopt this as the standard way of mocking
URL connections.

commit_message:
Replace HttpConnection in auth_token with Requests

Requests is becoming the standard way of doing http communication, it
also vastly simplifies adding other authentication mechanisms. Use it in
the auth_token middleware.

This adds the ability to specify a CA file that will be used to verify a
HTTPS connections or insecure to specifically ignore HTTPS validation.

SecurityImpact
DocImpact
Partial-Bug: #1188189
Change-Id: Iae94329e7abd105bf95224d28f39f4b746b9eb70

commit_message:
Added pagination for nova-manage vm list

In nova-manage, added an option, page_size, for vm list which
gets so many number of instances from database.
This option is defaulted to 100.

End user can choose to continue to get more
results or stop the command

Fixes bug 961317

Change-Id: I35e68880313bf1fa36326d4338fc8a5bcb3f96d8

commit_message:
Add a chapter on advanced configuration

This isn't a complete chapter, but it seemed like the logical way
to start adding coverage of periodic tasks. I'd be interested in
comments on this approach as this is my first doc patch.

Resolves bug 1107410.

commit_message:
Redirecting user back to previous screen

After browser session timeout, the user is now redirected back to the previous
screen upon login.
Also added a non regression unittest.

Change-Id: I995bc217803805364967688e9b896b9b54583b36
Closes-Bug: #1201619

commit_message:
Handle inst not found exceptions in pollsters

Updates the CPU/Net/Disk compute pollsters so we handle
instance not found exceptions. These types of exceptions may
occur when an instance has been deleted during sample processing.

Fixes LP Bug #1223098.

Change-Id: Icc8a79f8c23276b68aa27e758872ff80ad484061

commit_message:
Configure a Neutron specific service password.

Neutron was using the admin password definition rather than a service
password specific definition. This will break as soon as the admin
password and the neutron service password are different.

Change-Id: I188d75c5ab930e87d8ae24a48ee9f59317be6453

commit_message:
Make boot-stack's stackrc be metadata driven.

For now we're going to do credentials as Heat parameters, to break the
gordian knot of what-to-implement-first we're facing. As such the
in-instance credentials need to change to be source from Heat.
boot-stack in particular hardcoded 'unset' rather than consulting
metadata.

Change-Id: I35cc8d64fdc24d1fc57c0d0c25aabbe0eb83840d

commit_message:
Make admin-password configurable.

We use the admin password in in-instance scripts that configure e.g.
nagios from the cloud metadata, but production clouds will all have
unique passwords - it has to be a parameter.

Change-Id: I1f6c697ce27580fd669c7623e7fcea4c96ec62d0

Fixed backups so that they no longer fail when backup size is > 2GB

Fixed backups to correctly write all segments to swift before writing the
manifest. This enables backups of > 2GB to be written to swift.

Fixes: bug 1224642
(cherry picked from commit 013c62dc53e0cf15f007796d39ce2a47769dd248)

commit_message:
Don't use admin credentials in bootstack.

Log watching is convenient, but watching nova list has no need to be
in-instance, and we really don't want the cloud admin credentials in
the instance willy-nilly.

Change-Id: I3d1d1304403828e0af976faeab9dde63264c9685

commit_message:
Support client generate literal ipv6 auth_uri base on auth_host

This patch is for fix bug 1208784. Support keystone client generate
literal ipv6 auth_uri via provided auth_host, when the auth_uri is
None.

Fixes bug 1208784

Change-Id: I226881a35a74ef668d4cd1c6829a64c94ff185d9

commit_message:
Fix ovs_lib's issue of parsing flow proto field

When 'proto' other than 'ip' and nw_src/nw_dst are provided at the same
time, the proto parameter will be ignored.

Fixes bug: 1223668

Change-Id: Ie813e66995e2a9310ec4b48c0f7de673db2097f1

commit_message:
Expose the vendor_passthru resource

The vendor_passthru resource allow vendors to expose a custom
functionality in the Ironic API. Ironic will merely relay the message
from here to the appropriate driver, no introspection will be made in
the message body.

Change-Id: I81f6460da80d44ab879fa4cadfbc0021b38ec96f

commit_message:
Fix and enable gating on H703 - string localisation

Avoid using multi positional strings for localisation,
as those are hard to translate to various languages.
Also enable gating on H231 (which does not trigger).

Change-Id: Ie22cf781bcd5ce7562a5e61cf08fde816e7af86a

commit_message:
pass default l3_gateway_service_uuid if not specified

Previously, if one created an external network of type l3_ext and did
not specify the default_gw_service_uuid via --provider:physical_network
an exception would be raised on the backend as we need to specify the
l3_gw_service_uuid we want nvp to use.

Fixes bug: 1224660

Change-Id: I6312956528c17d6a704d4e4ef629916f6463312a

commit_message:
Avoid performing extra query for fetching qos bindings

Bug 1215872

Add a relationship with eager loading in the Port and Network models,
thus preventing the 'extend' functions from performing extra queries.
This patch also slight alters the methods for processing qos_queue
bindings in order to allow them for populating the qos_queue id in
the response being created.

Change-Id: Ie80d12aeed5de94afa61f23d7bcfc21372f23c4f

commit_message:
Clean up code of virt_phy_sw_v2 module

 Removes two methods not used:
 * _get_all_segmentation_ids
 * _validate_vlan_id

 About log formatting:
 * In the __init__, '\n' can be removed from this line:
     LOG.debug(_("Loaded device plugin %s\n"),

Closes-Bug: 1180783

Change-Id: Ic0aea7e8016f198e2ba245c710e12bc490720039

commit_message:
Add missing notifications for rescue/unrescue

The rescue and unrescue operations are missing start/end notifications for
the operation. Most Nova instance operations emit
compute.instance.<operation>.start/end notifications, which external systems
can use to track changes in the state on an instance (e.g. for billing
purposes). Rescues change launched_at for the instance, which can prevent an
external system from having a consistant picture of the instances' running,
unless they take that into account.

Change-Id: I3d7d334c88953ddf693c864c3e5e0746cdd2056c
Closes-bug: 1224088

This new method is attached to troveclient.flavors.Flavors.  However, generally speaking anything that has "mgmt" in the path gets its own class extending troveclient.base.Manager. So for example the calls which nest under mgmt/instance call don't live in the troveclient.instances.Instances class. I like this as it sort of communicates that the API paths are different (so heavy users of the CLI don't start thinking the normal flavors API has a create method).

I think there is some merit in moving this to a new flavors class- maybe it could be troveclient.management.MgmtFlavors.'}, {'account_id': 7806, 'date': '2013-09-04 18:58:12.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-09-04 19:44:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Works for me

commit_message:
Adds support for admin to create flavors through mgmt API

Extending the management API to allow for an admin to
create flavors categorized on service type in trove.

Change-Id: I8d5910e6dd9e497d1a8be4ffd58aa339d12db74f
Implements: blueprint service-type-filter-on-flavors

commit_message:
Added Trove (Database as a Service).

- Added changes to stackrc for the Trove Repos.
- Added support to devstack for "install", "configure",
  "init", and "run"

implements blueprint:trove-devstack-integration

Change-Id: Ib3f6daad33e629f764a174b80762c808ce8588e2

Would it be better to still have the vmdk in vmware_base and do a CopyDatastoreFile_Task or CopyVirtualDisk_Task to copy it over into the new directory from vmware_base for each new guest? [{'created': '2013-07-19 00:44:40.000000000', 'message': 'VMware image clone strategy settings and defaults.

The VMwareAPI driver code currently spawns all virtual machines
copying the disks using a linked-clone strategy by default.
The VMwareAPI also offers a "full clone" strategy. This patch
makes the following changes and improvements.

* default clone strategy to "full clone"
* allow images to specify if they are "linked_clone" or not.

For technical discussion on the clone strategies and their trade-offs
see: https://www.vmware.com/support/ws5/doc/ws_clone_typeofclone.html

Change-Id: I7a7ad57708202c8e8af5551b92a1e734185125f4

commit_message:
VMware image clone strategy settings and overrides

The VMwareAPI driver code currently spawns all virtual machines
copying the disks using a linked-clone strategy by default.
The VMwareAPI also offers a "full clone" strategy. This patch
makes the following changes and improvements.

* allow images to specify if they are "linked_clone" or not.

For technical discussion on the clone strategies and their trade-offs
see: https://www.vmware.com/support/ws5/doc/ws_clone_typeofclone.html

DocImpact: vmware_linked_clone metadata controls image-clone-strategy
Change-Id: I7a7ad57708202c8e8af5551b92a1e734185125f4
Blueprint: vmware-image-clone-strategy

commit_message:
Fix volume_connector host: use instance host IP

get_volume_connector is returning the IP for the host serving the SDK.
When using vCenter the SDK host and the hardware host may be different.
Using the vm_utils you can find the host for an instance easily.

fixes bug/1193980

Change-Id: I14b9c8f72a8ba0fccd437ee22f6cda256c5a4055

commit_message:
Use six string types instead of basestring

To increase our python3 compatability we should
attempt to use the six module for known issues
that are likely to happen in python3 when comparing
to string types.

Change-Id: Ib6fc32138e218c8b45023ca37d87b742694b8349

commit_message:
Remove Whitebox tests

This commit removes the whitebox tests from tempest. The proper place
for this type of testing is in nova unit tests not in tempest.

Fixes bug 1222852

commit_message:
Remove usage of oslo.db and oslo.config

Remove further reference to oslo-incubator database
layer which itself uses oslo.config and remove its
dependencies and resync with oslo-incubator after
applying these changes.

Implements blueprint eliminate-oslo-cfg

Change-Id: Ie1ee7affae75c60833c012c921e50d7b14026101

We don't need to update PO files of all languages.
PO files of languages other than English should be update by
importing translations from Transifex.

English PO files. This makes a patch updating PO files shorter
and helps reviewers to check it.

'}]
commit_message:
./run_tests.sh --makemessages update English PO files only

Closes-Bug: #1224388

We don't need to update PO files of all languages.
PO files of languages other than English should be update by
importing translations from Transifex.

This commit changes "run_tests.sh --makemessages" only updates
English PO files. This makes a patch updating PO files shorter
and helps reviewers to check it.

Change-Id: I5410a06b0bcb0f42c5a0853f95a3fe2087519d51

Instead of having a pretty restrictive module
based api for saving logbook objects it is much
more friendly and extensible to move toward a more
ceilometer-influenced engine and connection based
storage backend using stevedore to do the backend
loading instead of a custom registration/fetching
mechanism. This allows us to provide a base object
oriented backend api that can be easily inherited
from to allow for customized & pluggable backend
storage modules.

Implements blueprint stevedore-based-backends
Implements blueprint ceilometer-influenced-backends

commit_message:
Move toward using a backend+connection model

Instead of having a pretty restrictive module
based api for saving logbook objects it is much
more friendly and extensible to move toward a more
ceilometer-influenced engine and connection based
storage backend using stevedore to do the backend
loading instead of a custom registration/fetching
mechanism. This allows us to provide a base object
oriented backend api that can be easily inherited
from to allow for customized & pluggable backend
storage modules.

Implements blueprint stevedore-based-backends
Implements blueprint ceilometer-influenced-backends

Change-Id: Ib5868d3d9018b7aa1a3354858dcb90ca1a04055d

commit_message:
General readability improvements

* Expand 'Univ' to 'University' for correctness.
* Remove scattered instances of double-spacing between sentences so that guide is consistent.
* Use '—' instead of '-' to improve appearance of list items.
* Adjust preposition placements to improve grammar.
* Add an xref instead of advising reader to "read below" so that we do a better job of guiding the reader through the document.
* Remove stray, empty <emphasis> items to clean up code.
* Remove unnecessary hyphens to improve grammar correctness.
* Other minor grammar improvements.

Change-Id: I0dffd2e05cf89e4a9421512cb4e24a2ee242e21d

[{'created': '2013-08-28 22:30:03.000000000', 'message': 'Add a hacking rule for dashes with rand_name

This commit adds a new hacking check to ensure that we only ever use
a single dash inside of rand_name. If there are two or more dashes in
a row as the parameter for rand_name() the new check will fail. This
is to prevent failures in the output parser for cli tests.

Change-Id: I1d1c09ae8977b1d7133b8236b9db636e8d28ee13

commit_message:
Remove '--' from rand_name calls and enforce it

Having two dashes in the service name is uneccesary and looks
slightly weird in the logs, especially for the cli tests. This commit
just switches the -- to a single dash and adds a hacking check to
ensure uniformity to random names in the logs.

Change-Id: I1d1c09ae8977b1d7133b8236b9db636e8d28ee13

Improve the libvirt inspector vnic parsing so that it handles
a missing mac address gracefully. Previously a missing MAC
address (if possible) could cause an ugly AttributeError to
get logged to the Ceilometer log file.

Related to LP Bug #1221784.

Change-Id: Ia897b493c9a9493a3ed3d9c3cf54ca29ff944892
'}]
commit_message:
Improve libvirt vnic parsing with missing mac!

Improve the libvirt inspector vnic parsing so that it handles
a missing mac address gracefully. Previously a missing MAC
address (if possible) could cause an ugly AttributeError to
get logged to the Ceilometer log file.

Related to LP Bug #1221784.

Change-Id: Ia897b493c9a9493a3ed3d9c3cf54ca29ff944892

commit_message:
Verbose functional test request failures.

* test/__init__.py: Put safe_repr import/implementation here so that it
is available to functional and unit tests.

* test/functional/swift_test_client.py: When a request fails
record why that request failed, how many requests failed, and what the
request was when raising RequestError to aid in debugging. Makes use of
safe_repr from test/__init__.py.

* test/unit/common/test_constraints.py: Remove implementation of
safe_repr and use the implementation in test/__init__.py.

Change-Id: I6c957343fb4b8b95d3875fd5ca87b3cf28a5f47a

_swap_volume is called in cases where new volume file has
already been created.  Add VIR_DOMAIN_BLOCK_REBASE_RESUE_EXT
in the flags passed when calling blockRebase to allow

Change-Id: I704772ba4bfef474fc788d277c99ba016fb7883f
'}]
commit_message:
Add REUSE_EXT in _swap_volume call to blockRebase

_swap_volume is called in cases where new volume file has
already been created.  Add VIR_DOMAIN_BLOCK_REBASE_RESUE_EXT
in the flags passed when calling blockRebase to allow
the existing volume file to be written to.

Closes-Bug: #1218057

Change-Id: I704772ba4bfef474fc788d277c99ba016fb7883f

'}, {'account_id': 1030, 'date': '2013-09-12 06:19:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

The problem in this case was actually that 'fault' somehow got lazy loaded in the first place when it shouldn't have.  If that hadn't have happened, then we wouldn't have gotten this exception.

This: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/46108/ happens to address that part of this bug.

I agree with your change, too, as we wouldn't ever save a fault this way.  Although, there's a different change that merged earlier today that would just log these AttributeErrors. :)   So I think we're fixing something here like 3 different ways.  hehe."}, {'account_id': 5638, 'date': '2013-09-12 11:29:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Gotcha! thanks for the feedback Chris. Hopefully @DanSmith likes this change too.'}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2013-09-12 13:02:34.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I don't think that we should merge this. The problem is actually just that the _save_fault() method was mis-named. This just papers over the problem.

I think that instead of just ignoring missing handlers, we should require that they exist with an explicit pass, and log as a warning as my other patch does:

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/46104/"}, {'account_id': 5638, 'date': '2013-09-12 13:12:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Abandoned'}, {'account_id': 1030, 'date': '2013-09-12 19:18:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Yeah, I guess I do agree with Dan on this.  I just need him to tag bug 1223962 on his other review. :)'}]
