commit_message:
Fix AttributeError when saving object with Fault

skip any fields specified in the INSTANCE_OPTIONAL_NON_COLUMNS list
as we don't need to save them into the database.

Fixes LP# 1223962

Change-Id: I7f09a90c490f882cf10b0d6fc326a02cd6846107

[{'created': '2013-09-11 22:11:31.000000000', 'message': "Ensure audit tests don't cause unwanted errors

Because the audit code catches all Exceptions, bugs in the code, like
misspelled names, bad logic, can result in errors which don't cause
exceptions that kill the unit tests.

commit_message:
Ensure audit tests don't cause unwanted errors

Because the audit code catches all Exceptions, bugs in the code, like
misspelled names, bad logic, can result in errors which don't cause
exceptions that kill the unit tests.

Change-Id: Iac570273ae7f84de0b02f024b0e43704bfbb6e68
Signed-off-by: Peter Portante <peter.portante@redhat.com>

commit_message:
run-tests: fix MongoDB start wait

There's actually 2 lines that matches the current rule:

  [websvr] admin web console waiting for connections on port 30000
  [initandlisten] waiting for connections on port 29000

Let's make it more tighten.

Related-Bug: #1218488

Change-Id: I4ba56a7c2406a9851aa8087b4cabb0aa31698763

commit_message:
Catch exceptions from nova client in poll_and_publish

Ceilometer compute agent dies if nova client raises an exception while it is
retrieving server instances. This might happen e.g. when some OpenStack API is
temporarily unavailable

Fixes LP Bug #1218889

Change-Id: I808dcfae18d23240f8e095d6c97c8dede7dede8f

commit_message:
Ensure audit tests don't cause unwanted errors

Because the audit code catches all Exceptions, bugs in the code, like
misspelled names, bad logic, can result in errors which don't cause
exceptions that kill the unit tests.

Change-Id: Idb8e3b00a49863ab920161a46edb61a5c47fffe2

[{'created': '2013-09-05 20:25:20.000000000', 'message': 'Fix create user with LDAP user_enabled_mask

When the LDAP Identity backend was configured with user_enabled_mask set to
non-zero, the Keystone server would return the masked value (e.g., 512)
when a user was created rather than the actual enabled value (true or false), and
did not include the enabled_nomask value like it does when the user is retrieved
when listed or updated.

This change makes it so that the server returns the enabled value as a Boolean
as expected and also returns the numerical value in the enabled_nomask
attribute when the LDAP Identity backend is used and configured with
user_enabled mask set to non-zero and a user is created.

Change-Id: I8a22aec3377ffd335095e645c1b3d65008dd0cf2
Closes-bug: #1220945

rather than the actual enabled value (true or false).

Closes-bug: #1220945
'}, {'created': '2013-09-09 18:01:24.000000000', 'message': 'Fixes for user response with LDAP user_enabled_mask

This fixes a couple of problems with the returned user object
when the Keystone server when the LDAP Identity backend is
configured and the user_enabled_mask setting is not zero.

First, the returned user had the masked value (e.g., 512) when
a user was created rather than the actual enabled value (true
or false).

Second, the Keystone server was returning the enabled_nomask
attribute in the user entry when users were listed or updated.

This change makes it so that the server returns the enabled
value as a Boolean when a user is created. Also, the

Closes-bug: #1220945
'}]
commit_message:
Fixes for user response with LDAP user_enabled_mask

This fixes a couple of problems with the returned user object
when the Keystone server when the LDAP Identity backend is
configured and the user_enabled_mask setting is not zero.

First, the returned user had the masked value (e.g., 512) when
a user was created rather than the actual enabled value (true
or false).

Second, the Keystone server was returning the enabled_nomask
attribute in the user entry when users were listed or updated.

This change makes it so that the server returns the enabled
value as a Boolean when a user is created. Also, the
enabled_nomask attribute is not returned when users are
listed or updated.

Change-Id: I8a22aec3377ffd335095e645c1b3d65008dd0cf2
Closes-bug: #1220945

[{'created': '2013-09-12 03:06:53.000000000', 'message': 'Add group by statistics examples in API v2 docs

Fixes bug #1224222

There are currently no examples in the API v2 documentation that
show the user how to request statistics with the groupby parameter.
This patch adds examples and explains that period aggregation is
applied before group by aggregation.

commit_message:
Add group by statistics examples in API v2 docs

Fixes bug #1224222

There are currently no examples in the API v2 documentation that
show the user how to request statistics with the groupby parameter.
This patch adds examples and explains that period aggregation is
applied before group by aggregation.

Change-Id: I5561c4397d124e2976771b3a3b14d666a611351e

commit_message:
Fix regression issues with cells target filter

1) Skip scheduling if a cell filter already took care of it
2) Call build_instances or schedule_run_instance (deprecated) depending on
   which method the caller used.

bug 1224465

Change-Id: I391e1c4f288c9dc3e1308ee8c001a662e0f4c1b8

commit_message:
Remove bin/tempest script

The bin/tempest script was just an out of date copy of run_tests.sh.
There is no reason to keep 2 copies of the same script around so this
commit just removes the copy in bin.

Change-Id: I91bacade03d0b503d9c729b76048aa67f5f209fa

Should that recipe be refactored?'}, {'account_id': 6530, 'date': '2013-08-26 23:03:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

The openstack-ops-database cookbook is only a reference cookbook.  It is intended to provide an example of how one could leverage some of the database and stackforge cookbooks in the deployment of openstack."}, {'account_id': 7, 'date': '2013-08-26 23:36:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

Craig, the openstack-chef-repo is a reference implementation as well :) I think adding the openstack-ops-database recipe to these roles is correct...'}, {'account_id': 6530, 'date': '2013-08-27 00:41:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: No score

Yeah, I thought of that when I wrote the comment, though I was under the impression that we were in some ways treating them as separate references.

In either event, I am not particular about which direction we choose, but I think we probably need some better docs around all of this stuff. I can certainly try to help with that.

The reason I say this is that I have run across a number of users who have run into this precise scenario, and even though documented in the README's, it needs some additional color.  Folks are typically looking to roll this stuff out quickly, usually in a trial capacity, and I fear they are giving up early.

Perhaps a sprint to clean docs up prior to Hong Kong?  Would be awesome to outline the "Here's how you use all of this awesome stuff we have worked on the last 6 months" :)

Again, I can easily be swayed here...let's just make it easy for users to adopt.

Thanks Jay.'}, {'account_id': 26, 'date': '2013-08-27 01:15:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

[{'created': '2013-08-16 18:17:12.000000000', 'message': "Avoid shadowing NeutronException 'message' attribute

This patch removes the shadowing of the NeutronException.message
attribute, done by its children exceptions, by using 'msg_fmt' as the
name of the class attribute so we can actually use an exception objects
.message attribute.

Currently:

  >>> class MyException(NeutronException):
  ...     message = 'Foo %s'
  ...     def __init__(self, bar):
  ...         message = self.message % bar
  ...         super(NeutronException, self).__init__(message)
  ...
  >>> MyException('bar').message
  'Foo %s'
  >>> str(MyException('bar'))
  'Foo bar'

whereas, we obviously wanted:

  >>> MyException('bar').message
  'Foo bar'
  >>> str(MyException('bar'))
  'Foo bar'

For more details see: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/37354/

Change-Id: I304f31edec20b1293cf6c8de931415590fde6752

commit_message:
Avoid shadowing NeutronException 'message' attribute

This patch removes the shadowing of the NeutronException.message
attribute, done by its children exceptions, by using 'msg_fmt' as the
name of the class attribute so we can actually use an exception objects
.message attribute.

Currently:

  >>> class MyException(NeutronException):
  ...     message = 'Foo %s'
  ...     def __init__(self, bar):
  ...         message = self.message % bar
  ...         super(NeutronException, self).__init__(message)
  ...
  >>> MyException('bar').message
  'Foo %s'
  >>> str(MyException('bar'))
  'Foo bar'

whereas, we obviously wanted:

  >>> MyException('bar').message
  'Foo bar'
  >>> str(MyException('bar'))
  'Foo bar'

For more details see: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/37354/

Fixes bug #1212882

commit_message:
Replace old functional http.post call

The patch removes a leftover of the old http helper functions and moves
the check of self.conf.auth to the setUp method.

[{'created': '2013-09-11 23:46:54.000000000', 'message': 'Add basic tests for unordered_flow

Previously the unordered_flow had no basic tests
to ensure that its in maintained and working order,
we should at least have basic sanity tests for this

commit_message:
Use the verification in the engine when translating

When translating the patterns into there corresponding
actions we can at the same time (before the translation occurs)
verify that the patterns preconditions are validated.

Part of blueprint flow-verification

Change-Id: I603f79f9fb96f8a1d7e43440c666692805194a3e

commit_message:
Add basic flow sanity checking

Flows should be able to provide basic sanity checking that
verifies the items contained inside the flow can actually
be satisfied so we should start off with the basic dependency
checking & satisfiability for the linear flow and ensure that
in the unordered flow that all items inside that flow can be
only satisfied by items external to that flow.

Implements: blueprint flow-verification

Change-Id: I6ee426fea83793309e7c1201495d65dbd339c36b

modifies error message in adding security rule

Because the information on the type of input data
is outputted in "validate_ip_protocol" method,
I removed the information on the type and
modified error message.

in this file.

Looks like feature code... Should alarm-audit-api really be considered complete without that in ?'}, {'account_id': 2284, 'date': '2013-09-06 10:13:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

@ttx: the sqlalchemy driver is not feature-complete in any case (i.e. it's missing a couple other important features, in particular the ability to do metadata-based queries), so the recommendation would still be to use mongoDB when alarming is required.

So I think it would be OK to consider alarm-audit-api effectively done in the sense that it's supported for the storage driver that should be used in production, but to treat this patch as a "for completeness" addition.

I could file a corresponding bug along the lines of "Alarm history is not supported for sqlalchemy" if you'd prefer to have that for tracking purposes?

Cheers,
Eoghan'}, {'account_id': 2284, 'date': '2013-09-06 11:05:01.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: (4 inline comments)

@Svetlana: thanks for the careful review. However, there are couple of points on which your comments confuse me, so I'd appreciate it if you could clarify on the basis of my responses.

Thanks!
Eoghan"}, {'account_id': 308, 'date': '2013-09-06 11:26:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Update openstack.common.policy from oslo-incubator

This includes the following changes:
 64bb5e2f5 Fix wrong argument in openstack common policy

commit_message:
Fix sync test when localhost on port 80 is binded

- When localhost:80 was binding the tests was trying to connect into it.
- To test you can simply run sudo python -m SimpleHTTPServer 80 which
  should show :

  1.0.0.127.in-addr.arpa - - [06/Aug/2013 14:10:42] code 501, message Unsupported method ('DELETE')
  1.0.0.127.in-addr.arpa - - [06/Aug/2013 14:10:42] "DELETE /a/c/o HTTP/1.1" 501 -

  (the test was passing since 501 would raise ClientException).
  mock delete_object in the fourth test to fix that
- Refactor the code to use mock.patch as well.

Closes-Bug: 1208802
Change-Id: I5ddd4ac3a97879f51cf5883fcfc0fe0f0adaeff6

Cleanup tests imports so not relative

This change cleans up the imports in tests packages by changing
relative local imports to absolute imports per OpenStack hacking
guidelines.

[{'created': '2013-09-03 18:38:51.000000000', 'message': "Remove py33 from tox.ini until eventlet is ported

There is no point in trying to run the py33 unit tests until eventlet is
ported to Python 3. Meanwhile the expected failure means we get a bunch
of garbage and extra lag time when trying to run 'tox' before sending to
gerrit for review/CI checks.

Change-Id: I343e24e77e097a2249a7ace1903faeaed71d7393
"}]
commit_message:
Remove py33 from tox.ini until eventlet is ported

There is no point in trying to run the py33 unit tests until eventlet is
ported to Python 3. Meanwhile the expected failure means we get a bunch
of garbage and extra lag time when trying to run 'tox' before sending to
gerrit for review/CI checks.

Change-Id: I343e24e77e097a2249a7ace1903faeaed71d7393

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-09-06 17:43:07.000000000', 'message': 'Remove CA key password from cert setup

Keys are generated with the genrsa command. The key is only password
protected if the -des -des3 or -idea argument is provided (encrypted
with DES, triple-DES, or IDEA respectively). The password must be
supplied via the --passout argument otherwise it will be interactively
prompted for.

ISSUE: genrsa is never called with -des, -des3 or -idea therefore it's
never password protected. Nor is the -passout argument
provided. Therefore the ca_password option is pointless. If the
ca_password were actually used then genrsa should have been called
with "-des3 -passout pass:%(ca_password)s".

The key is then provided to the openssl req command. In order for the
req command to be able to read the key the password must be provided
via the -passin argument or it will be interactively prompted for.

ISSUE: -passin is never passed to the req command therefore it cannot
read a passord protected key non-interactively.

The openssl req command will attempt to password protect any key it
output's unless it's passed the -nodes argument. It only generates a
key if a key is not supplied via the -key argument.

ISSUE: The req command used when generating the signing cert is passed
-nodes but since req is not generating a key it has nothing to
encrypt hence it's pointless.

The openssl ca command needs the ca key in order to sign requests. The
ca may be encrypted with a password, if so it will need the ca
password to decrypt the key. The key password is passed via the
-passin argument, if the -passin argument is not provided it will
prompt for it interactively.

ISSUE: The openssl ca command is not passed the key password, if it
did it would need to so like this: "-passin pass:%(ca_password)s".
Since the ca_password is not passed to the ca command it's not
doing anything.

Passwords used by openssl are either prompted for interactively or
obtained non-interactively via a comman line argument, an environment
variable, a file, read from a file descriptor (e.g. pipe) or read from
stdin.

ISSUE: Since OpenStack components are meant to run non-interactively
(at least not requiring admins to type in passwords at random prompts)
we must store the password in the file system, typically inside a
config file. The only thing that protects that password are
DAC (Discretionary Access Control) commonly known as file
system protections and/or MAC (Mandatory Access Control) typically
implemented via SELinux. Since the protection on the key file is not
fundamentally different than the protection on the file containing the
password it's dubious as to what extra protection is being provided by
password protecting the key. In a properly configured system the same
protections should be applied to both the key file and the password
file. If an attacker has access to the one of the files he almost
certainly has access to the other file. This begs the question as to
what actual protection is being afforded via key passwords. In fact an
argument can be made that having to carefully protect configuration
files containing passwords is an additional security item which has to
be verified, something which adds complexity with marginal
benefit. More to the point many admins are not likely to understand
the critical importance of protecting a config file, while on the
other hand the necessity to protect a key file is obvious. Another
justification for removing the ca pasword is the keystone
configuration documentation (doc/source/configuration.rst) states keys
provided by an external source must not be password protected. So if
externally provided keys are not password protected they why would
keys generated by keystone-manage be password protected? It's
inconsistent.

Summary:

Given numerous mistakes in using key passwords in the current
implementation and the marginal value key password protection afford
it is recommended to eliminate password protection with the added
benefit of reducing the complexity of the system. Less complexity
usually results in greater security because there are fewer moving
parts to track and validate. As Bruce Schneier says "Complexity is the
worst enemy of security". The numerous mistakes in utilizing the
openssl password options is a testament to the complexity argument
especially considering the existing code passed a peer review
process.

Change-Id: Iaeb97f2338c4d3c6e770b410dee8f1b62778b561
Fixes: Bug #1214016
'}, {'created': '2013-09-09 16:19:59.000000000', 'message': 'Remove CA key password from cert setup

Password protection in the current implementation is not actually
applied despite the presence of the ca_password config
option. Password protection is of marginal benefit because the
password must be stored in a file using the same protections afforded
to the key file. Password protection currently is not utilized with
externally provided keys.

Remove the ca_password config option and remove the use of the various
password related options to the OpenSSL commands whose net effect was
not actually accomplishing anything.

See the bug report for a thorough description of the issues.

Change-Id: Iaeb97f2338c4d3c6e770b410dee8f1b62778b561
Fixes: Bug #1214016
'}]
commit_message:
Remove CA key password from cert setup

Password protection in the current implementation is not actually
applied despite the presence of the ca_password config
option. Password protection is of marginal benefit because the
password must be stored in a file using the same protections afforded
to the key file. Password protection currently is not utilized with
externally provided keys.

Remove the ca_password config option and remove the use of the various
password related options to the OpenSSL commands whose net effect was
not actually accomplishing anything.

See the bug report for a thorough description of the issues.

Change-Id: Iaeb97f2338c4d3c6e770b410dee8f1b62778b561
Fixes: Bug #1214016

* Adds instructions for using Vagabond to test the
Chef repository.

to Vagabond

added to the vagabond environment

commit_message:
Fixes misuse of assertTrue in compute test scripts

Misuse of assertTrue in places where assertEqual should be used.

If assertTrue is used instead of assertEquals, the test will always pass
if the first argument's boolean cast is True. The second argument
passed to assertTrue() will be regarded as the error message
when the assertion fails. Using assertEqual will actually check
if two arguments are same value.

Fixes bug #1220538

Change-Id: Ia3f033cd8c63e59bfe2387a477ef79dce7c0f102

commit_message:
Add expected_errors for extension aggregates v3

And remove some extra invalid params checking that
we didn't check in most of extensions. We can do
more strict checking when we have API input validation.

Fix bug 1214315
Partially implements bp v3-api-extension-versioning

Change-Id: I9c1f8265ea6e19e48cc2f8e747d04d3c3b66e55d

commit_message:
Fix v3 swap volume with wrong signature

Fix bug 1219672

Fix the signature and add related integrated test.
And fix test_servers missing subs 'glance_host'.

Change-Id: I040dafe2c1bcfc014fdeba3f735b322908af96c0

commit_message:
Fix live-migrate when source image deleted

We now cache the most import image details in system_metadata
so if we unable to access the image, fallback to the cached image data.

Fixes bug 1221200
Change-Id: I58244a01c72c1ab764710dbccff3a1b1bacea1fe

commit_message:
Fix cisco n1kv plugin cli option and help

Rename VXLAN option to OVERLAY and add help for sub-type field in
the Cisco N1kv specific cli to accomodate
cisco-plugin-n1k-enh-vxlan-support blueprint.

Change-Id: I4a3dc7ad1b45f6effebd6fd337c51e7c0eeba84c
Closes-Bug: #1220966

[{'account_id': 8091, 'date': '2013-09-04 21:53:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Nadya, this is very initial, with lots of debugging code :)  It took me quite a while to figure out how to do many-to-many relationships in sqlalchemy.

As a side note, ForeignKey constraints I believe are not working in our sqlite database.  I have read that they are turned off by default, and there is magic to turn them on.  The ForeignKey constraints on the association table to prevent JobBinaries from being deleted when referenced from a JobOrigin do not work in savanna -- however, in the FireFox plugin SQLite Manager with key constraints enabled dynamically, they do work.

I may do more later but I wanted to get this draft pushed so that at least you can see it in the morning.'}, {'account_id': 8091, 'date': '2013-09-04 22:02:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: (6 inline comments)

commit_message:
Add "mains" and "libs" fields to JobOrigins

These fields allow many-to-many relationships between JobOrigin
and JobBinary objects.

Co-Authored-By: Nadya Privalova <nprivalova@mirantis.com>

Implements: blueprint edp-resources-for-job

Change-Id: I8e01445d2e3f10704ae281fd1b1d67dfeadaf427

Nova now uses the 'database/connection' and
'database/idle_timeout' as the config section/names.

Some distro packages are starting to include default
connection settings using the new format so it is
important that we set it in puppet since using deprecated
format (sql_connection, etc) will not override the default
setting.
Change-Id: Iecb1c5fc8c44c7ab6a44de0d72b93b61780212c7
"}]
commit_message:
Move sql_ config opts into [database] section.

Nova now uses the 'database/connection' and
'database/idle_timeout' as the config section/names.

Some distro packages are starting to include default
connection settings using the new format so it is
important that we set it in puppet since using deprecated
format (sql_connection, etc) will not override the default
setting.
Change-Id: Iecb1c5fc8c44c7ab6a44de0d72b93b61780212c7

commit_message:
Config manager

The path introduces the CloudConfigManager class, intended for easy conversion
between python dictionary and configuration text file formats. The class also
containing the defaults values for the cloud config hardcoded.

CloudConfigManager inherits from the abstract ConfigManager; that's done
in assumption that later another ConfigManager, namely TestConfigManager class
will be developed.

Blueprint test-engine

Change-Id: I8ea61f18cedd6d586a6e9cf8ae73a34edabf4bb9

commit_message:
Revert "Check libvirt connection URI"

This reverts commit 7d2bfa814030b952dc221e808b652e2d1b15bf3a.

The virsh command is running as sudo across TOCI, so that change is not
needed and it's causing TOCI to fail when running on the server-side
(TOCI Jenkins).

Change-Id: Id9991a4bb9ff7410a8963b2f7aa6efe622780382

commit_message:
Convert devtest.md to devtest.sh.

We have an ongoing challenge with CI/toci : our user story
'devtest.md' is duplicated in the CI infrastructure. By using the well
known pattern of testable-documentation / documented tests we can have
cake and eat it too: a clear story that helps users understand whats
going on, and a script that can test our workflow end to end.

This will be a multi-part story to get the devtest aspects of toci
ported back into the main repository without compromising the docs -
this step sets up the framework, but devtest.sh isn't yet runnable.

Change-Id: If9c7a7b42c22a12799fed557117ad058f75ef6c2

overrideable. This formulation should work better.

commit_message:
Handle missing libvirt vnic targets!

Updates the libvirt inspector so that our vnic inspection
can handle cases where the interface/target is missing.
This can occur in some (usually transient) cases where
Nova is pausing/migrating/etc an instance.

Previously Ceilometer would functionally work fine but
a rather long stack trace would get logged to the log file.

Fixes LP Bug #1221784

Change-Id: I7113c6e4bb4af622d517915d13147f5912bad126

commit_message:
Register regexp testing function in yaql context for dynamic UI.

Function is called 'test', because it returns only True|False
(have matched or not). If we decide to implement another regexp
function, which matches groups for further referencing
(and thus returns list of strings or empty list), it should be
called 'match'.

Change-id for master branch commit is
I9e131fdd01fd4edbed269d911dce28354a4edb4e

Change-Id: Ic82c79a1f28a2d0e9256f0050746f8eedfa34708
Fixes: MRN-882.

The path //v1/account does not denote any Swift resource. More

commit_message:
Fix handling of bad paths in Swift middleware

The path //v1/account does not denote any Swift resource. More
importantly, if you call swift.common.utils.split_path() on it (as the
Swift middleware does), then you get a ValueError.

Since it's a bad path, it doesn't refer to any Swift resource, so
there's no stats to publish, so we can just catch and ignore
ValueError.

Change-Id: I9908beef8478c5407985435c1526a9c72edb1d3a

commit_message:
get_node_power_state will update DB when state out of sync

ConductorManager's get_node_power_state method asks the driver to check
a node's actual power state. In the event that the database record of the node's power state
is out of sync with reality, ConductorManager should attempt to update
the db.

Change-Id: I3dfa606bfffa0e6512f64645cad05e1248ec64de

[{'created': '2013-04-05 21:53:10.000000000', 'message': "Fix quota updating when admin deletes common user's volume

Add 'project_id=None' optional argument in QUOTAS related methods.

There are two problems when admin deletes volumes of common user
before fixing this bug:
Firstly, It will get tenant quotas using context.project_id which
results in getting admin's quotas not common user's.
Secondly, It will also get wrong quota usages using context.project_id
when updating common user's quota_usages.

So we could pass into QUOTAS related methods an optional argument to
specify the tenant ID to be affected. And if it's not set, then we
default to drawing the tenant ID from the context.

Fixes: bug 1078668
Change-Id: Ie250da84726d1c5c3280430038184000dfd1e9e2
(cherry picked from commit 576c9b0880c32bfc8053550b8f25a76df98c60e4)
"}]
commit_message:
Fix quota updating when admin deletes common user's volume

Add 'project_id=None' optional argument in QUOTAS related methods.

There are two problems when admin deletes volumes of common user
before fixing this bug:
Firstly, It will get tenant quotas using context.project_id which
results in getting admin's quotas not common user's.
Secondly, It will also get wrong quota usages using context.project_id
when updating common user's quota_usages.

So we could pass into QUOTAS related methods an optional argument to
specify the tenant ID to be affected. And if it's not set, then we
default to drawing the tenant ID from the context.

Fixes: bug 1078668
Change-Id: Ie250da84726d1c5c3280430038184000dfd1e9e2
(cherry picked from commit 576c9b0880c32bfc8053550b8f25a76df98c60e4)

commit_message:
Fix UpdateProjectMembersAction excess keystone calls

Patch adds a single call to keystone user_list with a specified project field
in place of polling all users roles to find out if they have any roles in the
current project.

Change-Id: Ia304af05cdb5be13e67762e0a0a44b17824c30bf
Fixes: bug #1224114

commit_message:
Fix three spelling errors

Discovered while performing translation:

'attempting' was misspelled in the two files patched here
'Network' was misspelled once

'en' PO file is also updated.
The update in PO file also includes the string update in commit 4609c7a9c.

Change-Id: I4d0eed02db74b152db4f599361f7df3e599ef5c6

Fixes: bug #1224365

commit_message:
Fixes files ordering when choosing newest image

For example if there are following kernels in undercloud/overcloud
image:
/boot/vmlinuz-3.9.5-301.fc19.i686.PAE
/boot/vmlinuz-3.10.10-200.fc19.i686.PAE
then disk-image-get-kernel picks vmlinuz-3.9.5. It should use the
newest one.

Change-Id: I7bbf06705e85370d66c7dd8a5d4f8d6c93b21c0c
Fixes: bug #1224365

commit_message:
Implement message controller.

This patchset contributes a message controller for Marconi client. It
implements simple property querying for messages, as well as the
ability to reload these properties as needed (polling?) and delete a
message. It also uses the assumed structure of the HTTPclient that
will form the basis of the connection from the common libraries.

six is used to boost py3k compat.

This also introduces a directory structure for supporting multiple
transports. Instead of having a 'controller' dir, now we have a
'transports/http' and 'transports/zmq'.

Author: Alejandro Cabrera
Implements: blueprint messages-management
Change-Id: I9d4e7c28939cdb68b74690e5c56e69d58ac1559a

commit_message:
Enable execution of heat-manage db_sync

This patch is aiming to correct a fault in puppet-heat that was not
executing the heat-manage db_sync that was making this module in the
end not fully working.

At this stage there are no tests wroted to support this change but
I am willing to add those in a later commit.

Change-Id: Iabd19ea3bcb2fa353367e3751f018695f6d28cf9

commit_message:
Fix race condition for test_flavors_extra_specs

Use rand methods to create flavor name and id so
parallel running of xml and json classes will not
fail with conflicting names.

Also fixes bug 1220034

Change-Id: I266f4a55e6f8c5a0e063164f656b09b4140c5866

commit_message:
Make the Swift-related doc more explicit

Thanks to Yassine Lamgarchal for noticing the documentation did not explicitely
state where 'ceilometer' must be found in the pipeline.

While we're at it, fix a typo: "these lines" should be used instead of "this
lines".

Change-Id: Iffff9b779d48bafefb249bba0f4db4a006f94a70

commit_message:
Catch generic exceptions

When the driver copy_image_to_volume fails it can
at the current time raise more than just CinderException
as its root exception type. This causes rescheduling due
to the blacklisted exception list that is used to determine
if a exception is 'bad enough' to trigger rescheduling or
should the volume creation action just set the volume to
error state.

To avoid the situation where this would cause a rescheduling
we should make sure (for now) that any exception that is
emitted on copying an image to a volume is translated
into a image copy failure and reraised.

Fixes: bug 1224211

Change-Id: Ia4a0a81d9e0967b1e7de07577d77084462304c60

commit_message:
Add provider option for setting token

This path is aim to add an option named provider
in [token], when token_format is set. In some situation.
if this option is not set, it will lead keystone fail to
start.

See ref here:
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/keystone/+spec/catalog-optional

Fixes bug #1223265

Change-Id: Idcad6892e11d47ffae0617a15fb65d7227c34b9a

Add py3kcompat from oslo to keystoneclient

This gives us a python version independent way of doing urljoins amongst
other things.

commit_message:
Log useful error message when pki_setup was not used

If openssl returns with error code (3), lets assume the
PKI certificate was not properly set up. Add a hint
to the logfile in that case.

  Forward port patch from David Höppner <0xffea@gmail.com>
  from keystone/common/cms.py

Change-Id: I80ebbe6d58283282af4a5cd0bf2e96a42ca7dead

commit_message:
Put all the debug output into stderr

When running unit tests of keystone, some test cases will
output debug information to stdout which will flood the
whole screen. It fixed the bug by redirecting the debug info
to the stderr and cleaning the original test output.

Fixes: bug #1134728
Change-Id: I49b64f8ae56ce5003cef6f2848fb807e30a97cc7

commit_message:
Remove unexpected console output of test_shell

The test_shell.py will generate output to stderr when test some
fake command, it is not so much useful message so i remove it via
redirect sys.stderr to stringio.

Change-Id: I8ddc77516a0a312194ca3a696f0648f592b67139
Fixes: Bug #1161849

commit_message:
test_servers_whitebox - using official client

1. using the python client libraries as the scenario tests.
2. move 403 to normal test cases as server could be terminated in any
   status
3. add wait_until_deletion_complete() in manager.py of scenario
4. set status_timeout() as a classmethod in scenario/manager.py so as
   to use it in other classmethod

Fixing Bug 1190309

Change-Id: I85979f1bc5ef7a35f111b293e17bdbb942603279

commit_message:
Add BlockDeviceMapping objects

This adds the objects BlockDeviceMapping and BlockDeviceMappingList
and switches a small block of ec2 API code to use them.

Related to blueprint compute-api-objects

Change-Id: I78e11c1f225f0aeaec30addc8585e89ed661517d

Seems reasonable. Stick a real commit message w/DocImpact on it, and I'll call it good."}, {'account_id': 1179, 'date': '2013-08-30 18:30:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

srly?

I was sorta *kidding* - is this even a good idea!?

Did anyone test some failures on a two replica cluster?  Shouldn't we make it configurable?"}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2013-08-30 18:45:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I dunno. I mean, right now, 2-replica clusters have known bad behavior and unknown bad behavior. This falls into the category of known-bad, I think, since you can't have even a single failure on write without torpedoing the request.

Yes, this means a 2-replica cluster will give you a 2xx on an object PUT even if it only wrote one replica. If you really cared about your data, you'd be running at least 3 replicas. 

I'm sure there's a bunch of other things wrong with 2-replica clusters too, and we'll get bugs for that as time goes on.

Also, since this doesn't affect 3-replica clusters at all, it's almost certainly not going to blow anything up for people with sane clusters, so it's low-risk to me.

Maybe I'm looking at it wrong, but it seems like this won't hurt me and might help others, so my opinion is about 10% "hooray" and 90% "meh".'}, {'account_id': 5189, 'date': '2013-09-03 02:01:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@Sam, I do know some local IPDC are using 2-replica + RAID5 but I don't know why they need this kind of setup..."}, {'account_id': 597, 'date': '2013-09-04 04:10:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

I think (n+1)/2 yields exactly the desired result, judging by the new test values. Am I wrong?"}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2013-09-04 18:45:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

@zaitcev: Yes, that looks equivalent. I'd write it with the integer division operator ("//") in case someone manages to call quorum_size with a float someday, but that may be overly paranoid.'}, {'account_id': 330, 'date': '2013-09-04 19:43:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Do not merge

Great idea, we should definitely talk about this in more detail about how to do effective 2-replica clusters (or N-replicas with storage policies).

For now, though, not this patch.'}, {'account_id': 9, 'date': '2013-09-12 06:03:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
Update BM API v3 to use UUID as client ID reference

Reworks the Nova Bare Metal driver API v3 to accept and return the UUIDs
instead of the database ID for Bare Metal Nodes.  This matches other
areas of the Nova API and is also useful when using the force_node
functionality as this requires UUID as input.

Fixes bug 1184447

Change-Id: I8e04ddf31d8aa47c509ef799daea206e5cf3256f

commit_message:
cinderclient API version validation

cinderclient/client.py added a method get_volume_api_version_from_endpoint()
to check cinder version from the endpoints. The code needs to be
flexible in order to handle different forms of endpoint URLs.
Here are the possible endpoint URLs:
http://{host}:{port}/v1/any/resource
http://{host}:{port}/some-base-url/v1/any/resource
Closes-Bug: #1214225

Change-Id: I9c976386206eae62cdeccd35c1286a8e883a1895

commit_message:
Use correct admin tenant for OrchestrationManager

OrchestrationManager currently uses the admin username
and password but the non-admin tenant name.  This ensures
tenant name is also pulled from the correct admin credentials
in config.

Change-Id: I2c6af9e78b3b3a7d8bc855c228ed0495e7b59382

Enable instance to use pure v6 subnet

Update network-related utilities to support pure v6 subnet
in IPv4 enviroment.

Fixes: bug 1209118

commit_message:
Clearify manual image creation

Responding to disqus comments, I noticed that the guide is not clear
that the manual image creation is done locally and includes an upload
step.

- Removal of checks prior to send commands in order to limit sollicitations to rootwrap
-Added fine grain check of VXLAN support to check if multicast or unicast-flooding must be used for broadcast emulation
-Added deletion of unused bridge

The two last funtions still lack of UT, but the rest of the code is quite functionnal and may be tested.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-09-06 19:50:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Works for me

This code is ready to merge, I'll review the OVS Agent and base L2 population code next. Nice work Sylvain!"}, {'account_id': 1689, 'date': '2013-09-11 18:58:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(1 inline comment)

Amazing work! This has the same ml2 import issue as the OVS agent patch. Once that is resolved, I'm OK with merging this. But a couple concerns come to mind:

First, I'm not clear why the VXLAN support is in the same patch as the L2 population support. Couldn't these have been separated? Given the FFE, I'm OK with them being combined, but I'd hate to see an issue with one prevent the other from going in (or requiring it to be backed-out).

Second, this is a substantial enhancement to linuxbridge-agent, and comes close to providing parity with openvswitch-agent (just needs GRE I think). Long term, I'm wondering if we need to continue to invest in both agents and maintain this parity. In what situations is linuxbridge-agent preferred over openvswitch-agent? Maybe this is a good icehouse summit topic?"}, {'account_id': 105, 'date': '2013-09-11 19:25:11.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

rkukura: I agree on, once the agents have parity, perhaps it's time to combine them, especially in the context of ML2. This is something we should discuss at the Icehouse Summit."}, {'account_id': 6820, 'date': '2013-09-11 20:31:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7: (1 inline comment)

I admit it should have been cut in separate patchsets, but I didn't wanted to add even more dependencies and make review more complex given the short delays.

You're both right regarding ML2 agent. This change can be seen as a proof of concept to show how new kernel features can be leveraged. But for sure it would be great if best of both implementations (OVS & kernel) could be used from a single new ML2 agent!"}, {'account_id': 1689, 'date': '2013-09-11 21:11:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7: (1 inline comment)

As I said, I'm OK with these being combined for now so we can get them into havana via the existing FFE.

A modular L2 agent supporting OVS as well traditional Linux bridging was part of the original ML2 proposal, was dropped from the havana plan, and definitely could be revisited for icehouse.

But my question is, now that much more of OVS has been properly integrated into the Linux kernel, is there still a compelling requirement to provide an alternative to OVS? Do we still need an option for older systems, and for how long? Are there other reasons to use traditional bridging in preference to OVS?

Looking forward to an updated patch!"}, {'account_id': 6820, 'date': '2013-09-11 23:31:03.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 8.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-09-11 23:59:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: Works for me

Build succeeded.

'}, {'account_id': 6820, 'date': '2013-09-12 00:11:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

OVS patch was added as a depedency to prevent merge confict as both are changing the same line in neutron/plugins/ml2/drivers/l2pop/constants.py.

@Bob, I'd advocate that linux bridging still has some key arguments to be supported alongside OVS in a future ml2 agent:
It is mainlined while in-kernel OVS datapath lacks some features, and DKMS module isn't shipped in all distros
VXLAN implementation is really feature rich, here we already have an ARP responder, so that there shouldn't be much broadcast or flooding between quantum ports, only unicast VXLAN trafic. It'll be more complex to add this feature to OVS. The module also supports distributed routing using the same commands (fdb and neighbor tables) using specific 'router' bridge fdb command arg.

For sure, we can't do whatever we want with dataplane as in OVS, but it seems to bring the right features to build a scalable overlay, without having to play with complex flow rules as in OVS."}, {'account_id': 105, 'date': '2013-09-12 00:25:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8: Looks good to me (core reviewer)

Nice work! And @feleouet, I agree with all your comments around LinuxBridge and it's viability as an overlay mechanism."}, {'account_id': 6820, 'date': '2013-09-12 00:51:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8: (1 inline comment)

Just figured there was a samll nit in l2_population support reporting. Thought it's not used in plugin for now, I'd rather resubmit to match OVS way of reporting status.

@kyle: thanks for your approval, hope to see it again in the next patchset."}, {'account_id': 6820, 'date': '2013-09-12 00:52:34.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 9.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-09-12 01:21:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9: Works for me

commit_message:
Vxlan / L2population support to Linuxbridge Agent

This patch introduces VXLAN support for Linuxbridge agent alongside
with ml2 plugin support in linubridge mechnism driver.

A new vxlan configuration section is added for vxlan related parameters.

The agent also implements l2population RPC callbacks which allows ml2
plugin using l2population mechnism driver to populate vxlan forwarding
and neighbor tables following portbinding events. It allows agent to
respond locally to ARP requests for remote VMs and avoid dataplane based
learning. This should help limiting the use of multicast or flooding
for broadcast emulation in vxlan networks.

These changes should anyway have a limited risk, as agent behaviour
shouldn't be affected, except when vxlan is enabled alongside ml2 plugin.

Implements: blueprint l2-population

Change-Id: I99a961c53f9e451409f1affb079042936d8ae5c6

Added batch insertion of flows (only used for fdb_add/remove RPC callbacks)
Added an option to instruct the agent to use fdb_add/remove RPC callbacks instead of tunnel_sync/update. On the one hand, it enables l2-population mechanism driver to coexist with previous tunnel_sync/update callbacks and enables agents using different configuration to interoperate (and thus allows their migration). But on the other hand, it may be weared to carry and ml2 mechanism driver related option within OVS agent...

Following localrc options may be used to test this patch:
Q_PLUGIN=ml2
Q_ML2_PLUGIN_MECHANISM_DRIVERS=l2population
Q_ML2_TENANT_NETWORK_TYPE=vxlan,gre
Q_AGENT_EXTRA_SRV_OPTS=(l2_population=True)'}, {'account_id': 6820, 'date': '2013-09-02 22:59:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: (2 inline comments)

commit_message:
OVS agent implementation of l2-population

This patchset implements l2-population RPC callbacks in OVS agents,
it enables plugin to populate forwarding table following portbindings
events.

For now, it doesn't include ARP responder implementation which is
deferred to a future patchset (As this feature isn't yet supported by
OVS, it will require the use of an external responder such as ebtables)

It anyway brings some improvements in tunnelling management, as agent
will tear-down unecessary tunnels, and flood packets on a per-network
basis rather than to all other agents.

These changes should anyway have a limited risk, as tunnel management
won't be affected as long as l2_population option is not set. This
option must be used in conjonction with ml2 plugin using l2population
mechanism driver.

Implements: blueprint l2-population

Change-Id: I5185eefedb0ff392bc8b99d16f810813e26ff58d

(10 inline comments)

First, I apologize for being so late with this feedback. I think this is very good work, and I'd like to see it get into havana.

My main issue is that I think we should consider a much simpler approach to notifying the mechanism drivers about changes to port status. Rather than add new driver_api methods, and their support in the manager and plugin classes, why not just change rpc.py to use plugin.update_port() to change the status? This way, drivers would see the status changes in the same way they see updates to any other port attributes. Also, there could be mechanisms that do not use L2 agents and/or RPCs, and would be using different mechanisms to update port status.

It seems to me that update_port() should be solely responsible for all port attribute changes, and the existing update_port_precommit() and update_port_postcommit() methods should allow mechanisms drivers to detect the changes. This is the approach I took in the ml2-portbinding implementation - mechanism drivers can see changes in the binding state because they always happen as part of a port update."}, {'account_id': 7141, 'date': '2013-09-05 06:04:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 33: (13 inline comments)

commit_message:
Add l2 population base classes

This patch initiates the blueprint l2-population
Implemented as a ml2 Mechanism driver.

OVS & LinuxBridge drivers will be added as dependencies.

Rebased on ML2 Portbinding.

Change-Id: Ia2345aa262ec791c9f38b6e41e1e4b46f69cadac

[{'created': '2013-09-03 19:35:36.000000000', 'message': 'Push sleep() down into DiskFile class for reads

As a sister-commit to Ibc4ac672 (https://review.openstack.org/44901),
hide the cooperative iterator hook, given that the only other consumer
of this was the auditor, which does not need it. The only consumer of
DiskFile is the REST API layer of the object server, which always wants
that cooperative behavior on reads (as well as writes).

commit_message:
Push sleep() down into DiskFile class for reads

As a sister-commit to Ibc4ac672 (https://review.openstack.org/44901),
hide the cooperative iterator hook, given that the only other consumer
of this was the auditor, which does not need it. The only consumer of
DiskFile is the REST API layer of the object server, which always wants
that cooperative behavior on reads (as well as writes).

Change-Id: Iec5e1d524adb39658afe16e893341a8372eb65ff
Signed-off-by: Peter Portante <peter.portante@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Skip secgroup rules invalid id tests until bug 1182384 is fixed

There are some existing reviews which try to deal with bug 1182384:

nova: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/35285/

tempest: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/29899/

There is also a mailing list discussion about this (see the link in the
bug report).

Until there is consensus on how to fix this, skip the compute tests if
neutron is available.

(cherry picked from commit 1d3f88580cee74ee127dac8b854dc545c04c28eb)

Conflicts:
	tempest/tests/compute/security_groups/test_security_group_rules.py

Change-Id: I3f0d21c23661f556354c321476ba559d4925dccd

commit_message:
Add link to why we have to make this factory due to late binding

Since python decorators do not at the time of decoration have
access to there instance that they are attached to we can't create
the functor task out of the method at the time of decoration but
instead we have to create a factory and late bind a functor task
to the function that was decorated for the function that was wrapped
to be executed correctly.

Change-Id: I8951ff036061ee18caaf38f10fb7ce6745433d91

commit_message:
Allow the lock decorator to take a list

In the cases where a list of locks is desired
to be acquired it would be nice to use the same
lock decorator to accomplish this.

Change-Id: Ib25329eef330d1b434bc3e8e79d7bb38f450c7ae

The version template defines the prefix for each build version that does not
change automatically, and a final suffix that changes on each interim release
candidate built. This commit set that prefix to the Havana release prefix,

'}]
commit_message:
Modify version template for the final OpenStack Havana release

The version template defines the prefix for each build version that does not
change automatically, and a final suffix that changes on each interim release
candidate built. This commit set that prefix to the Havana release prefix,
which required being able to accommodate versions such as this aa.bb.cc.dd
instead of just aa.bb.cc as before.

Change-Id: I983efb7f0c2407351d276c6ed80bfa0e98587828

commit_message:
Remove heat::db class

heat::db is different to every other project's puppet modules.  All of
nova, glance, keystone and cinder take a "sql_connection" parameter to
the "main" (project name) class.

This removes heat::db and adds it into init.pp to maintain parity with
those projects.  This seems more logical than adding it to engine.pp;
since heat-engine is only using the DEFAULT section of heat.conf.

Change-Id: I4584cdb12d1f9e624228e6ee34b4bcfbf649a12e

'}, {'created': '2013-08-23 15:11:33.000000000', 'message': 'Driver check during node update process implemented

Fixes: bug#1207124.

Currently, the ConductorManager is not testing a change to the node.driver, leading to the following unexpected behavior:
1. create a node with a valid 'driver' parameter
2. update the node with an invalid 'driver' parameter -- PATCH '{"driver": "foobar"}'
3. try to update the node with a valid 'driver' parameter -- PATCH '{"driver": "fake"}'
4. observe failure to load the "foobar" driver here.

To fix this case I added try_load_driver method to NodeManager that finds driver by driver name and returns it. If driver would be found DriverNotFound exception would be raised.
Additional check for driver changes and changes for driver_info was added to awoid processing driver_info with incorrect driver.

Change-Id: Ibfb4df973464f132c0c135edea71f586d1c871e9

commit_message:
Driver's validation during node update process implemented

Currently, the ConductorManager is not testing a change to the
node.driver, leading to the following unexpected behavior:
1. create a node with a valid 'driver' parameter
2. update the node with an invalid 'driver' parameter
    -- PATCH '{"driver": "foobar"}'
3. try to update the node with a valid 'driver' parameter
    -- PATCH '{"driver": "fake"}'
4. observe failure to load the "foobar" driver here.

To fix this case was added try_load_driver method to NodeManager
(at ironic/conductor/resource_manager.py) that finds driver by driver
name and returns it. If the driver isn't found a DriverNotFound
exception is raised.
Additional check for driver changes and changes for driver_info
was added to ironic/conductor/manager.py:ConductorManager.update_node
to avoid processing driver_info with incorrect driver.
Tests for NodeManager(init and load_driver) functionality was
added.

Fixes: bug#1207124.
Change-Id: Ibfb4df973464f132c0c135edea71f586d1c871e9

commit_message:
Optimization reserve and release nodes db api methods

Bulk queries used for replacement one-by-one cycles.
Complex operations executed only in the case of error.
add_filter_by_many_identities() method added.

Change-Id: I3161f5ace1fa5b1bee76cda48700218b64e2b79e

commit_message:
Remove all non-existent db recipes from roles

Right now this example repository references recipes that are no
longer present. Database configuration and table creation is not
handled by these respositories and have, therefore, been removed.

Change-Id: Iaf40343bf871a603477bea4c61e7930ac40113a3

commit_message:
Remove general 'unauthorized' message from middleware

The message is too general to be useful, and at this late stage it
could override a more useful message that may have been provided
earlier.

Change-Id: If819748f765ce30a71206a15f9874727e459dce8
Closes-Bug: #1221716

The list of image formats has become customisable, but didn't have a
default which can cause issues since it's a required field when
creating a new image. Also document the setting.

Additionally, mark OpenStack settings documentation as "(Partial)"
until #1221115 is closed.

Change-Id: I980c2d61bc9f9ac14fa39e5088c2ce03c48499b2
Closes-Bug: #1223427

commit_message:
Provide a default for OPENSTACK_IMAGE_BACKEND

The list of image formats has become customisable, but didn't have a
default which can cause issues since it's a required field when
creating a new image. Also document the setting.

Additionally, mark OpenStack settings documentation as "(Partial)"
until #1221115 is closed.

Change-Id: I980c2d61bc9f9ac14fa39e5088c2ce03c48499b2
Closes-Bug: #1223427

commit_message:
Remove keep_data_fp argument from DiskFile constructor

All access to the data_file fp for DiskFile is moved after the new "open"
method.  This prepares to move some additional smarts into DiskFile and reduce
the surface area of the abstraction and the exposure of the underlying
implementation in the object-server.

Future work:

 * Consolidate put_metadata to DiskWriter
 * Add public "update_metdata" method to DiskFile
 * Create DiskReader class to gather all access of methods under "open"

Change-Id: I4de2f265bf099a810c5f1c14b5278d89bd0b382d

commit_message:
import lib/oslo so we can clean it up

we were calling cleanup_oslo, however we weren't importing
lib/oslo, so that was just throwing an error message and moving on.

Let's stop doing that and actually clean up oslo.

Change-Id: I48340a8b3d5b50477fb5a7e2ce0bed27deb3ec01

commit_message:
Fix asymmetric view of object fields

This adds an obj_fields property which returns a combined view of the
real field key names as well as the extra_fields. This will help
avoid bugs where we forget to consider extra_fields.

Change-Id: I93351ccc9f87817deca06e9a2d94f82a3dd5f51a
Closes-bug: 1223888

I have posted two cleanup patches I663cf1c994307160c9f0ebf51fa4c920f2b6125e and I4e2ebd099b7373948c82abf86615a85db055c7c5.

Their patches will make this test case simpler.
So if they are merged before this patch, could you apply them to this test case?
If this test case is merged before them, I will do by myself :-)"}, {'account_id': 6796, 'date': '2013-08-16 12:06:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

thanks for updating the commit message

I like the disk content check (performed from within the instances) you're introducing with this test but again, I suggest we improve the existing TestVolumeSnapshotPattern scenario rather than add a new one.

By doing so we will be avoiding the duplication of similar steps from the two separate scenarios and also create something which supersedes the scope of both.

We will indeed:
. ensure the image is cloned from glance into a bootable volume (a shared step)
. ensure an instance is correctly booted from the volume (a shared step)
. ensure the the volume is writable (from your case)
. ensure we can create a volume snapshot (from the existing case)
. ensure we can boot an instance from the snapshot based volume (from the existing case)
. ensure the disk changes are visible into the newly created snapshot based volume (from your case)

what would be otherwise the benefit of stripping this down into a check performed twice against the same backing volume, like you're currently proposing?"}, {'account_id': 7203, 'date': '2013-08-20 08:30:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: (1 inline comment)

Hi, Kenichi.

Thank you for your comment.

Hi, Giulio.

1. About duplication steps

I think we should move shared steps to OfficialClientManager.(e.g. https://review.openstack.org/#/c/42593/4 )

By doing this, the duplication steps will be removed from the both tests.

2. About where to add a test

I think I can merge this test to your test.
However, I want to check booting a instance twice from a single volume.
This scenario does not take a snapshot. So, I think it is wrong to add the test to VolumeSnapshotPattern.
Therefore, I think that we should create this test in a new file.'}, {'account_id': 6796, 'date': '2013-08-20 09:30:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

@Yuuichi: how about we add there also a step which stops the first instance and boots a new one, from the same volume, before we take the snapshot then? we can then perform the disk contents check on both the volume (from the secondly booted instance) and the snapshot (from the thirdly booted instance)'}, {'account_id': 7203, 'date': '2013-08-21 07:14:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

Hi, Guilio.

I think it is good.
However, I want to rename the file name and the class name, because the name brings a little confusion.
VolumeSnapshotPattern seems to do the test of snapshot only.  

The class name will be renamed from VolumeSnapshotPattern to VolumeBootPattern.
The file name will be renamed from test_snapshot_pattern.py to test_volume_boot_pattern.py.'}, {'account_id': 6796, 'date': '2013-08-21 09:52:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

@Yuuichi: agreed, thanks!'}, {'account_id': 7203, 'date': '2013-08-23 06:05:04.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 7203, 'date': '2013-08-23 06:06:37.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

commit_message:
Append some operations to boot from volume pattern

The follow operations added:
* Write content to a volume and check written content
* Boot a instance twice from a single volume

This patch rename the class name and the file name.
Because, the name brings a little confusion.
VolumeSnapshotPattern seems to do the test of snapshot only.

Change-Id: I549934c4cd412ac88961f113d037235cc177d3fd
Related-bug #1210437

commit_message:
Python3: Use six.StringIO for io.Bytes()

The newer version of six (1.4.1) provides six.StringIO which
is a fake file object for textual data. It's an alias for StringIO.StringIO
in python2 and io.StringIO in Python3.

Use the fake object where approiate.

Change-Id: I364001933b4f2305ac27b293a9a4a3fec36c8a49
Signed-off-by: Chuck Short <chuck.short@canonical.com>

Soooo... not to throw a spanner in the works here, but changing FnGetRefId() to return self.physical_resource_name()  instead of self.name (or even just calling physcial_resource_name() instead of FnGetRefId()) would solve the problem in a much simpler way (i.e. without adding another key). Though you'd have to substitute the '-'s for '_'s if ceilometer won't allow them."}, {'account_id': 7075, 'date': '2013-09-04 16:18:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

It's was proposed on patchset 1 & 4 something you propose but didn't work here!
At the end, a new attribute is the simpler way.

We need to tag instances with a unique 'string' per group and in same time we also need to get this same unique 'string' from templates to create Alarm rule  ( via 'Ref' or 'Fn::GetAtt').

No concensus to determine what FnGetRefId() must return name or ARN but anyway
 if FnGetRefId() return an ARN we need to substitute ':' by '_' .. and the 'Ref' will be no more valid. 

For the use of physical_resource_name, it is composed of user data (name of the resource) which can have a '-' .. AND 'Ref' mustn't return "stack.name _  rsrc.name _ short_id(rsrc.id)" according to the aws doc.

Hope this clarify your point of view.'}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2013-09-05 10:16:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

Thanks, I had missed that earlier discussion.

However, the most important thing for AWS compatibility is how it works, not how it looks.

If we have to return something from FnGetRef() that looks like a physical resource name instead of an ARN - even if it doesn't look like any of our other physical resource names because of s/-/_/ - then that is merely unfortunate. (In fact, almost all of our resources differ from AWS in this respect, because our default is to return the physical resource uuid, not the physical resource name.)

However, if templates don't work the same, then that is a really bad incompatibility problem. And that appears to be the case here.

The standard example (http://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSCloudFormation/latest/UserGuide/aws-properties-cw-dimension.html) for setting up an AWS::CloudWatch::Alarm resource looks (in part) like this:

      "Dimensions": [
         {
            "Name": "AutoScalingGroupName",
            "Value": { "Ref": "WebServerGroup" }
         }
      ],

In Heat we implement that resource type as a provider template comprising an OS::Metering::Alarm resource, which translates the "Dimensions" property to fit the matching_metadata field.

So, not only will existing CloudFormation templates not work properly (which is to say, they'll work but still exhibit this bug), but to get them to work you would need to implement something like:


      "Dimensions": [
         {
            "Name": "metering.GroupId",
            "Value": { {'Fn::GetAtt': [ "WebServerGroup", 'GroupId' ] }
         }
      ],

which is a Heat extension, so you could not even create a working Heat template that could also work on CloudFormation.

As AWS compatibility goes, this is 1000x worse than a RefId in a different format. I don't consider the RefId format part of the API, but the ways you can validly use a RefId are definitely part of the API.


So my suggestion would be to implement:

    def physical_resource_name(self):
        pn = super(InstanceGroup, self).physical_resource_name()
        if pn is not None:
            return pn.replace('-', '_')

    def FnGetRefId(self):
        return self.physical_resource_name()

and this fixes the bug for both native and AWS resources.'}, {'account_id': 7075, 'date': '2013-09-05 13:15:13.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

You're right for the compatibility it's worse and I like your suggestion !

I'll push it if everybody is ok to change InstanceGroup.FnGetRefId() to return physical_resource_name().replace('-','_')


Note about ceilometer: 
- The charactere ':' is always problematic : not used with your suggestion so ok.
- Ceilometer can be happy with some '-', but I have found at least one case where he is not : with an UUID in the query (4a80714f-0232-4580-aa5e-81494d1a4147). So is safer to replace '-'"}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2013-09-06 14:03:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: (1 inline comment)

Ceilometer bug has been raised after discussion with ceilometer folks (eglynn and dhellmann):

https://bugs.launchpad.net/ceilometer/+bug/1221736

When this is fixed I think we should be able to pass an ARN or "-" delimted identifier, depending on which version of the AWS docs we decide to believe, just using the physical resource name seems OK to me, but without needing any s/-/_ mangling.

I also agree the priority is template level compatibility, with interface alignment a desirable additional goal.'}, {'account_id': 7135, 'date': '2013-09-06 14:24:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

I definitely agree that the template compatibility is the most important thing, and Zane's suggestion seems good.

Regarding the AWS docs,  the one that Steven refers to seems more appropriate according to the information on intrinsic-function-reference-ref.html page - "For more information about Ref return values for a particular resource or property, refer to the documentation for that resource or property.".  Sorry for making the confusion.'}, {'account_id': 7075, 'date': '2013-09-06 14:27:11.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

Thanks all.
I'll push a patch with physical resource name without replacement."}, {'account_id': 7075, 'date': '2013-09-06 15:43:54.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 8.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2013-09-06 16:11:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8: Works for me

This attribute is used to tag instances of a group and

   'metadata.user_metadata.GroupId' : {'Fn::GetAtt': ['WebServer', 'GroupId']}}

commit_message:
Use physical_resource_name as Ref for Instance/AS Group

This allows to distinguish groups by stack when using resource
OS::Metering::Alarm with the rule:
matching_metadata: {
    'metadata.user_metadata.groupname': { 'Ref': 'WebServerASGroup'}}

And add test for AutoScalingGroup Tags

fixe bug #1215840

Change-Id: If3de5c4abddcfb49f711db223a0c1a8c70f3c15a

commit_message:
Clean up object comparison routines in tests

Many object tests have the need to gracefully compare a
dict-like DB object with a NovaObject. That entails common
things like ignoring datetime timezones, etc. All of that
was duplicated in each test, but slightly tweaked. This
adds a common routine for that on the base test and makes
the other tests use it instead.

Change-Id: I6d5f0cdb8ee4d86addaec5315c55ab3a24276c9d

commit_message:
Sync with the requirements repo

Ensure that taskflow syncs with the openstack
requirements repo so that our requirements will
match requirements with the other projects we
integrate with (who also use the same requirements)

- Adjust hacking issues due to requirements update
  as well.

Change-Id: I1b03aa1650e7fd5e77c99c29a68ec0e3ec08c457

'}, {'account_id': 4992, 'date': '2013-05-31 02:16:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

(1 inline comment)

Could we add test where we give wrong passphrase.

Did you get rid of volume type extra specs .. was it necessary.'}, {'account_id': 6802, 'date': '2013-05-31 16:27:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: (3 inline comments)

Adding a test for the wrong passphrase requires moving away from the "fake" command execution to create an actual encrypted volume and then attempt to unlock it. Utilities like cryptsetup will exit abnormally if an incorrect passphrase is supplied; the abnormal exit causes an exception to be raised, which aborts the attachment of the volume.'}, {'account_id': 4992, 'date': '2013-06-01 19:40:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Thanks Joel for clarification that dmcrypt will throw exception on wrong passphrase.

Curious, how does dmcrypt check that it has been given a passphrase versus a random key string? presence of blanks?
would mot our random string generated from a high entropy system be more secure. I am guessing the original passphrase stemmed from people using short passwords perhaps from dictionary.'}, {'account_id': 6802, 'date': '2013-06-03 15:35:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Our current implementation uses LUKS, which stores a hash of the passphrase on disk. Regular dm-crypt without using LUKS has no way to validate the passphrase so the volume will be mounted but decrypted incorrectly (i.e., the contents of the mounted volume should look like random bytes).

More details regarding LUKS are available in the following two papers:
1) TKS1 - An anti-forensic, two level, and iterated

So I am generally OK with this going in like this if we want to get the feature for Havana as it does looks good enough. I do have a couple of points (that I probably should have brought up earlier but I missed this patch :( ). Most are about the way the encryption internal interface with the driver is designed:
 -This will only work for attaching volumes but not when booting with those volumes. this tells me that passing volume_info to a attach is not the best way to design this data flow as we can't do the same for boot (we need info for each volume etc). What would be ideal is to add hooks for encryption to block device objects added in https://review.openstack.org/#/c/39086/. Additionally we could encapsulate the device path fiddling there as well and have a much cleaner API. This can of course be refactored later.
 - I don't like the way how context is being passed to attach covertly - we should add it to the method signature - there is no reason we can't change that.
 - It would maybe be good to use entrypoints/stevedore for loading encryptors, as this seems to be where nova is going wrt to loading code.

Refactoring as outlined in the first point would have a number of benefits as it would allow us to make encryption driver-agnostic. Unless I am missing something - there is nothing virt driver specific with it.

I will not approve the patch as I am not sure it's OK to land based on the commit message - but +2 for getting it into Havana and fixing it later."}, {'account_id': 6802, 'date': '2013-08-26 12:57:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10:

Passing the context and encryption metadata to the attach method signature won't be an issue. I should have an updated patch ready within the hour.

I'll also look into stevedore for loading the encryptors. Is this change something that we can refactor following acceptance (like the refactoring around block device objects)?

> I will not approve the patch as I am not sure it's OK to land based on the commit message
You didn't comment explicitly on the commit message... What would you like changed apart from the removal of text regarding the related Cinder changes?"}, {'account_id': 6802, 'date': '2013-08-26 15:01:36.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 11.'}, {'account_id': 6802, 'date': '2013-08-26 15:03:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11:

I will add some inline comments about some minor issues I believe we can improve on if we agree to grant an FFE on this.'}, {'account_id': 6804, 'date': '2013-09-06 19:59:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 16:

[Nova] FFE Request: Encrypt Cinder volumes
We request that volume encryption [1] be granted an exception to the feature freeze for Havana-3.  Volume encryption [2] provides a usable layer of protection to user data as it is transmitted through a network and when it is stored on disk. The main patch [2] has been under review since the end of May and had received two +2s in mid-August.  Subsequently, support was requested for booting from encrypted volumes and integrating a working key manager [3][4] as a stipulation for acceptance, and both these requests have been satisfied within the past week. The risk of disruption to deployments from this exception is minimal because the volume encryption feature is unused by default.  Note that the corresponding Cinder support for this feature has already been approved, so acceptance into Nova will keep this code from becoming abandoned.   Thank you for your consideration.

The APL Development Team

[1] https://blueprints.launchpad.net/nova/+spec/encrypt-cinder-volumes 
[2] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/30976/ Change I358813b3: Add encryption support for volumes to libvirt
[3] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/45103/ Change Ia6f4c69e: Add key manager implementation with static key
[4] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/45123/ Change Ie9ab9578: Synchronize the key manager interface with Cinder'}, {'account_id': 1849, 'date': '2013-09-09 16:18:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 16:

volumes during the attach call. Created a new VolumeEncryptor class that is
responsible for encrypting volumes. The default implementation does not do
enryption, and a DmCryptVolumeEncryptor is provided to encrypt volumes using
dmcrypt.

Implements: blueprint encrypt-cinder-volumes

SecurityImpact

volumes during the attach call. Created a new VolumeEncryptor class that is
responsible for encrypting volumes. The default implementation does not do
enryption, and a DmCryptVolumeEncryptor is provided to encrypt volumes using
dmcrypt.

This feature requires related changes within Cinder (e.g., storing encryption
key UUIDs for encrypted volumes), which have not yet been accepted. This patch
is fully functional but is will require further modifications (that are

commit_message:
Add encryption support for volumes to libvirt

Add support to encrypt Cinder volumes. Hooks within the libvirt
driver encrypt volumes during the attach call. Created a
VolumeEncryptor interface as well as several concrete subclasses
(e.g., CryptsetupEncryptor and LuksEncryptor) to handle encryption.

This feature depends upon related changes that have been accepted
into Cinder (e.g., storing encryption key UUIDs for encrypted
volumes).

Implements: blueprint encrypt-cinder-volumes
Change-Id: I358813b3ecde4f88de7202c1c07d9b1168c2c332
SecurityImpact

commit_message:
Clean up duplicated change-building code in objects

Almost every object thus far has done this:

  changes = {}
  for key in self.obj_what_changed():
      changes[key] = self[key]

to get a dict of updates to apply to the database. This patch adds
that as part of the base object and makes every place that does
the above to just use that.

Change-Id: I847f5d35181b0305668b107f86faa164e71c3375

commit_message:
Impose a size limit on JSON request body

The size limit on JSON request body is to ensure the server not being
overwhelmed by extremly large JSON request body.

Fixes bug #1215501

Change-Id: Ia58f6690e994d34212953c44821f7a4cc4c435fe

commit_message:
Make v3 API console-output extension core

Adds the console output extension to the core list for the V3 API
Renames os-console-output to console-output as part of this change

+DocImpact

Partially implements blueprint nova-v3-api

Change-Id: I947e4bd70192d6f95b598f591aa0546f86c88653

revisions:
[{'created': '2013-08-29 18:37:16.000000000', 'message': "fix: Requests get slower when queues have a lot of messages

The primary culprit was an additional scan operation
in the MongoDB driver's _list(...) method, triggered by
a range query on the message's expiration date.

This patch removes that field from the query, and wraps
the cursor with a generator to filter out expired
messages that are returned. This should save a lot os
ms waiting for the response of the query from the DB.

Also in this patch, the order of the project and
queue name fields were swapped in the index in order
to optimize for selectivity. In addition, some minor
edits were made for style and correctness.

Change-Id: Ie4bd125e966612f4a8022fd6af133314d05fe428

commit_message:
fix: Requests get slower when queues have a lot of messages

The primary culprit was an additional scan operation
in the MongoDB driver's _list(...) method, triggered by
a range query on the message's expiration date.

This patch removes that field from the index, so the filtering
is done using a single scan pass. It also removes 'e' from the
index used for counting messages, since in testing it was
slightly faster to leave it out (and should also slightly speed
up insertion time since it's once less index field that mongo
has to worry about.)

Also in this patch, the order of the project and
queue name fields were swapped in the index in order
to optimize for selectivity. In addition, some minor
edits were made for style and correctness.

Finally, this patch also removes thresholding from
the GC so that we don't have expired messages hanging
around for a long time that have to be filtered out.

Change-Id: Ie4bd125e966612f4a8022fd6af133314d05fe428
Closes-Bug: #1216950

commit_message:
Add check for deprecated method assert_

The proper one is assertTrue, assert_ is deprecated as of 2.7.

There were some projects using assert_().
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/44456/

This patch will prevent code from deteriorating.

Change-Id: Id6f0ed85eb62d6ea9a1f352427882743cc3a7101

commit_message:
Upgrade memory recommendations to 2G everywhere.

I spent some time profiling today, and a huge chunk of time was just
in IO thrashing, a little more memory helps quite a bit. (But more
would be better, but we'll run out of memory if we aren't careful...)

Change-Id: Ib02bc859668b77017ce10f671976389a65e94330

commit_message:
MultiprocessWSGITest wait for workers to die bug

MultiprocessWSGITest.test_terminate_sigterm
fails because the wait for workers to die is unreliable.

Parent process can now wait on child or grand-child
processes to complete before moving on. This allows
for grand-child (aka worker) processes to take as much
time as they need to shutdown. NOTE: If the processes
still take too long, they will be killed by the test
framework throwing the "TIMEOUT" exception.

Fixed pep8 issue with python3

closes bug #1218133

Change-Id: I0d2e34463860a8fa59d6eef0ffbf63341a002e3d

commit_message:
Python3: Fix traceback while running unit tests

While running the unit tests with python3 the following
traceback appears:

TypeError: can't use a string pattern on a bytes-like object

This is due to the way that python2 and python3 handles unicodes.

Change-Id: I401f1cefed69780073222cae98d8da4c3d8031a8
Signed-off-by: Chuck Short <chuck.short@canonical.com>

commit_message:
Man page lintian errors and warnings

Used groff to recreate the errors. I believe all the issues
except `binary-without-manpage` are solved. Would like
confirmation from someone using Lintian.

Closes-Bug: #1210114
Change-Id: I533205c53efdb7cdf3645cc3e3dc487f9ee5640a

Remove cases of 'except Exception' in tests.image

except Exception can hide unrelated bugs, we shouldn't use it when
possible.

Change-Id: I5a8e3db8788e7a7b17b58a6c2c3999cf9a04e325
Partial-Bug: #1223605

commit_message:
Log pre and post test hooks to file and stdout.

* devstack-vm-gate-wrap.sh: Redirect stderr into stdout, pipe the whole
thing through tee to log to a file and stdout when running the pre and
post test hooks in devstack gate.

Change-Id: Iba86ad3f5f64264cd5670248ba18422a0afd0efe

Improve unittest coverage of account reaper

Add more unittests for account_reaper in order to
improve code coverage.

Fixes: bug #1210045

I think I addressed/responded to most comments. However I kind of disagree with the part that make dispatch calls based on router-type. Details are inline. Initially I thought it is easy change. However when I thinking how this can be done I found that for some functions it is easy but for other it is not so, as some logics are more complex and have dependency functions of the plugin itself (and I don't think we would want to put plugin as a argument to these dispatch calls either).

I agree this is the perfect, but among these two options I would prefer using the function override and supercall rather than dispatch API calls."}, {'account_id': 6461, 'date': '2013-08-29 19:27:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 13:
